It is transmitted by the lone star tick (Amblyomma americanum) through tick-borne transmission. The symptoms of human granulocytic anaplasmosis include headache, muscle aches, fatigue, fever, and rash, outlining a condition that significantly impacts the infected individual's health.

Moreover, it is transmitted by ticks, specifically the union of Ixodes pacificus, Ixodes ricinus, and Ixodes scapularis. HME is associated with symptoms such as rash, headache, fever, fatigue, and muscle aches. It is also known by the synonym Ehrlichiosis chafeensis.

The infection manifests with symptoms such as fever, eschar, and maculopapular rash. This comprehensive definition encapsulates its transmission vectors, causative agent, and clinical manifestations.

Astrakhan spotted fever is a type of spotted fever that primarily has a material basis in Rickettsia conorii and is transmitted by tick-borne transmission methods. Specifically, transmission involves ticks such as Rhipicephalus pumilio and Rhipicephalus sanguineus. This fever is characterized by several symptoms, including fever, maculopapular rash, and eschar. Additionally, Astrakhan spotted fever is defined as a spotted fever caused by Rickettsia conorii subsp caspia, transmitted by ticks (Rhipicephalus pumilio and Rhipicephalus sanguineus). The infection manifests with symptoms such as fever, a usually single eschar, regional adenopathy, and a maculopapular rash on the extremities.

Indian tick typhus is a type of spotted fever that has its material basis in at least some Rickettsia conorii and is defined by having a material basis in Rickettsia conorii subsp indica. Additionally, the infection is characterized by fever, eschar, regional adenopathy, and a maculopapular rash on extremities.

The symptoms of this disease include fever, eschar, and a maculopapular rash. The definition of Israeli tick typhus emphasizes that it is a spotted fever caused by Rickettsia conorii subsp israelensis, transmitted by Rhipicephalus sanguineus ticks. The infection manifests with symptoms such as fever, eschar, regional adenopathy, and a maculopapular rash on extremities.

Flinders Island spotted fever is also known by the exact synonym Thai tick typhus and the related synonym FISF.

Japanese Spotted Fever is a type of Spotted Fever, and it is also known as Rickettsia Japonica Spotted Fever or Oriental Spotted Fever. It has a material basis in Rickettsia Japonica and can be transmitted by ticks, specifically Haemaphysalis Flava and Dermacentor, through tick-borne transmission. The symptoms of Japanese Spotted Fever include fever and eschar. According to a definition, this spotted fever is caused by Rickettsia Japonica, transmitted by ticks such as Dermacentor taiwanensis and Haemaphysalis Flava. The infection results in symptoms like fever, eschars, regional adenopathy, and rash on extremities.

Rickettsia parkeri spotted fever is a type of spotted fever that primarily has its material basis in Rickettsia parkeri. It is transmitted by the Gulf Coast tick, Amblyomma maculatum, and through tick-borne transmission. This condition is characterized by several symptoms, including rash, headache, fever, and eschar. Furthermore, Rickettsia parkeri spotted fever is precisely defined as a spotted fever that results from Rickettsia parkeri and is spread by the Gulf Coast tick, Amblyomma maculatum, presenting with fever, headache, eschar, and rash. It is also known by its exact synonym, maculatum infection.

Rocky Mountain spotted fever is a type of spotted fever and has an exact synonym "Tick typhus." It is defined as a spotted fever with a material basis in Rickettsia rickettsii, transmitted by ticks, specifically Dermacentor variabilis and Dermacentor andersoni. This infection is also characterized by symptoms such as fever, headache, abdominal pain, and a maculopapular rash that can progress into a papular or petechial rash. Additionally, Rocky Mountain spotted fever is associated with a material basis in Rickettsia rickettsii and is transmitted through tick-borne transmission, including Dermacentor variabilis, Dermacentor andersoni, and other forms of tick-borne transmission. The fever's symptoms include abdominal pain, headache, fever, maculopapular rash, and papular rash.

Rocky Mountain spotted fever is also known by several related synonyms, including Brazilian spotted, Choix, Exanthematic typhus of Sao Paulo, Fiebre maculosa, Fiebre manchada, Sao Paulo typhus, So Paulo fever, and Tobia fever, indicating its recognition and identification across different regions and languages.

Oropharyngeal anthrax is a type of gastrointestinal anthrax, which is defined as a gastrointestinal anthrax that results in an infection located in the mucosa of the oropharynx. It has a material basis in Bacillus anthracis, transmitted by the ingestion of anthrax-infected meat. This type of anthrax has several symptoms including lesions, vomiting of blood, severe diarrhea, and loss of appetite. Additionally, oropharyngeal anthrax is associated with symptoms such as some loss of appetite, severe diarrhea, diarrhea, vomiting, and hematemesis.

Erysipeloid is a primary bacterial infectious disease that encompasses several key characteristics. Firstly, it has a material basis in Erysipelothrix rhusiopathiae, indicating the bacterial cause of this condition. Additionally, it is transmitted through contact with infected animals, highlighting the mode of transmission as contact transmission. The disease manifests in the skin, where the infection leads to symptoms such as redness, tenderness, and warmth of the skin. This comprehensive definition encapsulates the nature, cause, transmission, and symptomatic presentation of erysipeloid.

Adiaspiromycosis is identified as a primary systemic mycosis, which is fundamentally a fungal infection. This infection can be located in the lungs or skin, leading to a disseminated granulomatous pulmonary process and cutaneous infection in rodents, small wild mammals, and humans. The material basis for adiaspiromycosis includes Chrysosporium parvum or Emmonsia crescens. Furthermore, the disease is known to particularly affect the lungs and skin.

Invasive aspergillosis is a type of aspergillosis and lung disease that essentially has a material basis in some form of Aspergillus. This particular disease is characterized by several features, including symptoms of hemorrhage, and it mainly affects the lungs. Moreover, invasive aspergillosis is known to have pneumonia as a significant disease feature. It is defined as a serious fungal infection of the lung with pneumonia caused by Aspergillus, which can spread to other parts of the body through the bloodstream in patients with acute leukemia and recipients of tissue transplants, with clinical symptoms that encompass pulmonary nodules and hemorrhage.
Keshan disease is a type of nutritional deficiency disease characterized by cardiomyopathy secondary to selenium deficiency, which serves as its definition.

Tinea barbae is a type of skin disease and dermatophytosis that primarily affects the bearded areas of the face or neck. It is a condition with a material basis in either Trichophyton mentagrophytes or Trichophyton verrucosum, which affects not only the horny layer of the epidermis but also the hair and nail. This disease is characterized by inflammatory kerion-like plaques and the formation of noninflammatory superficial perifollicular pustules. It specifically targets the stratum corneum of the epidermis and other skin zones. Tinea barbae is also known by the exact synonym "dermatophytosis of beard".

Ectothrix infectious disease is classified as a type of hair disease and falls under tinea capitis. It is characterized by its material basis in Trichophyton verrucosum and Trichophyton equinum, indicating it originates from these fungi. The disease specifically affects the strand and cuticle of hair, highlighting its targeted location within the hair structure. Furthermore, ectothrix infectious disease is defined as a tinea capitis that results in a fungal infection located in the cuticle of hair. This condition is caused by several fungi, including Microsporum canis, Microsporum gypseum, Trichophyton equinum, and Trichophyton verrucosum. These fungi produce arthroconidia on the exterior of the hair shaft, which is a distinctive feature of the disease.

Endothrix infectious disease is categorized as a type of hair disease, specifically a form of tinea capitis. It is classified under conditions that have a material basis in certain Ascomycota, indicating its fungal origin. Moreover, this disease is associated with locations such as strands and cuticles of hair. By definition, endothrix infectious disease is a tinea capitis characterized by a fungal infection located in the hair, which is caused by Ascomycota fungi. These fungi are part of a group known as dermatophytes, distinguished by producing arthroconidia within the hair shaft exclusively.

Tinea imbricata is a type of tinea corporis and also a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some Trichophyton concentricum. It is defined as a tinea corporis that results in a fungal infection located in the skin, has a material basis in Trichophyton concentricum, and is characterized by ring-like growth in overlapping circles that may have an autosomal dominant genetic predisposition.

Disease by infectious agent is synonymous with infectious disease and is identified by OBI 9991118 as infectious disease. It is a type of disease defined as a disease that results from the presence of pathogenic microbial agents, which include pathogenic viruses, pathogenic bacteria, fungi, protozoa, multicellular parasites, and aberrant proteins known as prions. Furthermore, disease by infectious agent is equivalent to a condition that intersects with diseases and conditions that necessarily have a material basis in entities that are either viruses, bacteria, eukaryotes, or prions.

La Crosse encephalitis is a type of viral infectious and brain disease that has a material basis in the La Crosse virus. This disease is transmitted by the Ochlerotatus triseriatus, commonly known as the treehole mosquito. La Crosse encephalitis is characterized by several symptoms, including paralysis, seizures, headaches, coma, and fever. Notably, the disease primarily affects the brain. It is also defined as a viral infectious disease that results in inflammation located in the brain, caused by the La Crosse virus, and transmitted by the treehole mosquito, Ochlerotatus triseriatus. The infection manifests with seizures, headaches, fever, coma, and paralysis. Furthermore, La Crosse encephalitis is known by several exact synonyms, including California Encephalitis, California virus encephalitis, and Neuroinvasive California encephalitis virus infection.

Hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis is a type of lymphatic system disease that exhibits symptoms such as hepatosplenomegaly, enlargement of lymph nodes, and lymphadenopathy. It is defined as a lymphatic system disease characterized by an expansion of the monocyte-macrophage population and intense hemophagocytosis. This condition can occur de novo or more commonly in the setting of another disorder, typically an infection or a malignancy. It presents with a clinical picture of fever, hepatosplenomegaly, lymphadenopathy, and peripheral pancytopenia, with the morphologic hallmark being the phagocytosis of hematopoietic elements by morphologically normal macrophages. Hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis is also precisely known as haemophagocytic syndrome.

Dengue Shock Syndrome (DSS) is a type of dengue disease that represents the most severe form of dengue fever. It has its material basis in the Dengue virus, with four serotypes (Dengue virus 1, 2, 3, and 4), which are transmitted by the bite of Aedes mosquitoes. Dengue Shock Syndrome is characterized by symptoms such as bleeding, hypotension, epistaxis (nosebleeds), shock, nasal bleeding, and gum bleeding. Additionally, the infection is known for causing easy bruising, blood spots, bleeding gums, and nosebleeds. It involves circulatory collapse, hypotension, narrow pulse pressure (less than or equal to 20 mm Hg), or frank shock, occurring after two to six days of initial symptoms. This leads to collapse, weak pulse, and blueness around the mouth.

Sinusitis is a type of paranasal sinus disease and it is categorized by various symptoms including weakness, congestion, fever, cough, and fatigue. It is defined as a paranasal sinus disease that involves inflammation of the paranasal sinuses which can arise from bacterial, fungal, viral infection, allergic, or autoimmune issues. The symptoms of sinusitis encompass fever, weakness, fatigue, cough, congestion, and it may also lead to mucus drainage in the back of the throat, known as postnasal drip.

Secretory diarrhea is a type of diarrhea and is characterized by at least having some symptoms of diarrhea. It is defined as a condition where there is an increase in active secretion or an inhibition of absorption, leading to little to no structural damage. The most common cause of secretory diarrhea is a cholera toxin that stimulates the secretion of anions, especially chloride ions.

Osmotic diarrhea is a specific type of diarrhea characterized by the occurrence of diarrhea when excessive water is drawn into the bowels. This condition can arise from various causes, including maldigestion issues such as pancreatic disease or Coeliac disease, where nutrients remain in the lumen attracting water. Additionally, osmotic laxatives, which are intended to relieve constipation by pulling water into the bowels, can also lead to osmotic diarrhea. In some cases, healthy individuals may experience osmotic diarrhea and bowel distention due to consuming high amounts of magnesium, vitamin C, or undigested lactose, especially if they ingest an unusually large quantity of dairy products without having lactose intolerance. Moreover, osmotic diarrhea is not only a type of diarrhea but also indicates that this condition can present symptoms of both diarrhea and constipation.

Motility-related diarrhea is a type of diarrhea that falls under the category of conditions with at least the symptom of some diarrhea. It is defined as a type of diarrhea caused by the rapid movement of food through the intestines, known as hypermotility. This rapid transit through the gastrointestinal (GI) tract means there isn't enough time for sufficient nutrients and water to be absorbed.

Inflammatory diarrhea is a type of diarrhea and also falls under the category of conditions that at least have diarrhea as a symptom. It is defined as a gastrointestinal system infectious disease that involves diarrhea occurring when there is damage to the mucosal lining or brush border. This damage leads to a passive loss of protein-rich fluids and a decreased ability to absorb these lost fluids. The condition can arise from various causes including bacterial infections, viral infections, parasitic infections, or autoimmune problems such as inflammatory bowel diseases. Additionally, tuberculosis, colon cancer, and enteritis are also potential causes of inflammatory diarrhea.

Superficial mycosis is a type of fungal infectious disease and also a type of condition that necessarily has a material basis in some fungi. It is defined as a fungal infectious disease that results in infection of the outermost layer located in the skin or in the hair shaft, has a material basis in fungi, and is characterized by the fact that no living tissue is invaded, and there is no cellular response from the host. Additionally, superficial mycosis has exact synonyms, including "Steroid-modified tinea infection" and "piedra."

Cutaneous mycosis is a type of fungal infectious disease and something that at least has a material basis in some fungi. It is defined as a fungal infectious disease that results in the infection of the keratinized layers located in the skin, hair, or nail, which extends deeper into the epidermis. It has a material basis in Fungi and results in the formation of skin lesions.

Subcutaneous mycosis is a type of fungal infectious disease, which is characterized by infections that are located in the skin or subcutaneous tissue. This disease has its material basis in fungi, which can penetrate the dermis or even deeper layers during or after a skin trauma. Furthermore, subcutaneous mycosis affects areas that encompass both the zone of the skin and the hypodermis, illustrating its wide-ranging impact within these regions.

Systemic mycosis is a type of fungal infectious disease defined as a condition where there is an infection of internal organs and tissues within the human body. This disease has its material basis in Fungi, which enter the body through various routes such as the respiratory tract, the gut, paranasal sinuses, or the skin. Once inside, they spread through the bloodstream to multiple organs.

Podoconiosis is a type of elephantiasis and is defined as an elephantiasis characterized by lymphedema located in the lower extremities, caused by a genetically determined abnormal inflammatory reaction to mineral particles in irritant red clay soils derived from volcanic deposits.

Acute diarrhea is a type of diarrhea and also falls under the category of conditions that at least have the symptom of some diarrhea. It is defined as a diarrhea that is of rapid onset and course, characterized by frequent loose or liquid bowel movements. Furthermore, acute diarrhea is a common cause of death in developing countries and ranks as the second most common cause of infant deaths worldwide.

Intestinal botulism is a type of botulism and a type of something that is transmitted by some vehicle-borne ingestion. It is defined as a botulism that involves intoxication caused by botulinum neurotoxins (BoNTA, B, E, and F) in adults. This condition has a material basis in Clostridium botulinum A, Clostridium botulinum B, Clostridium botulinum E, and Clostridium botulinum F. These bacteria are transmitted by the ingestion of bacterial spores, which then grow in the intestine and release toxins.

Asymptomatic dengue is a type of dengue disease, which is a type of condition that, at the very least, has a material basis in some dengue virus. It is defined as a dengue disease that results in infection, has a material basis in the Dengue virus [NCBITaxon:12637] with four serotypes (Dengue virus 1, 2, 3, and 4), and is transmitted by the bite of an Aedes mosquito. Notably, the infection does not manifest any symptoms.

Kartagener syndrome is a type of primary ciliary dyskinesia and has an exact synonym, Kartagener's syndrome. It is defined as a primary ciliary dyskinesia characterized by sinusitis, bronchiectasis, and situs inversus with dextrocardia, resulting from the dysfunction of the cilia during embryologic development.

Adenoiditis is a type of upper respiratory tract disease characterized by inflammation, pain, and swelling of the adenoid tissue due to infection by bacteria and viruses. It primarily occurs in children and can be secondary to an allergy, infection of the nose or throat, or an obstruction of the eustachian tube. The symptoms of adenoiditis include pain, dysphagia (difficulty swallowing), and swelling. Additionally, redness is also a symptom of the infection. It is also known by its exact synonym, chronic adenoiditis.

Otomycosis is a type of otitis externa, which is defined as an otitis externa that is a disease of the ear produced by the growth of fungi in the external auditory canal. It is characterized by inflammation, pruritus, scaling, and severe discomfort, with the most common fungi being Aspergillus niger and Candida albicans. Additionally, otomycosis has the exact synonym "Singapore ear."

Laryngotracheitis is a type of upper respiratory tract disease defined as an upper respiratory tract disease involving inflammation of both the larynx and trachea, often caused by a viral infection. This infection can close off the windpipe.

Pontiac fever is a type of legionellosis characterized by a milder respiratory illness without pneumonia. It is transmitted at least through droplet spread and presents symptoms such as headache and fever. These symptoms typically last for 2 to 5 days.

Aspiration pneumonia is a type of bacterial pneumonia that is defined as an acute pulmonary inflammatory response developing after the inhalation of colonized oropharyngeal material containing bacteria. It is observed in individuals with dysphagia and gastric dysmotility. This disease displays symptoms such as tachypnea and cough. Additionally, aspiration pneumonia is associated with symptoms including dysphagia and tachypnea.

Pulmonary aspergilloma is a type of aspergillosis and a type of lung disease, characterized by its material basis in some aspergillus and its location in the lungs. It is defined as an aspergillosis that presents as a clump of tangled mass of Aspergillus fungus fibers, blood clots, and white blood cells, existing in the cavities of the lungs that develop in an area of previous lung disease or lung scarring.

A sensory system disease is equivalent to a condition characterized by the intersection of a disease and a condition that, at a minimum, is situated within the sensory system. Additionally, a sensory system disease falls under the category of a nervous system disease. It is defined as a nervous system disorder that occurs in the portion of the nervous system tasked with processing sensory information. This includes sensory receptors, neural pathways, and brain regions involved in the perception of senses. The well-known sensory systems affected include those responsible for vision, hearing, touch, taste, and smell.

Idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis is a specific type of pulmonary fibrosis characterized by scarring of the lung. This condition is part of a broader category that fundamentally arises from an intersection involving abnormal pulmonary interstitial morphology and scarring, with the disease specifically located in the lung. Furthermore, idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis is precisely known by other names, including fibrocystic pulmonary dysplasia, idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis, familial, and cryptogenic fibrosing alveolitis.

Cryptogenic organizing pneumonia, also known by its exact synonyms including BOOP, Cryptogenic organising pneumonitis, Cryptogenic organizing pneumonitis, bronchiolitis obliterans organising pneumonia, bronchiolitis obliterans organizing pneumonia, cryptogenic organising pneumonia, and idiopathic bronchiolitis obliterans with organising pneumonia, or idiopathic bronchiolitis obliterans with organizing pneumonia, is a type of idiopathic interstitial pneumonia. This condition is characterized by lung inflammation and scarring that obstructs the small airways and air sacs of the lungs (alveoli). The onset of cryptogenic organizing pneumonia, which is heralded by symptoms such as a flu-like illness with a cough, fever, a feeling of illness (malaise), fatigue, and weight loss in about 50% of affected individuals, often features the frequent presence of crackling sounds (called Velcro crackles) when a doctor listens with a stethoscope. Additionally, it is associated with symptoms including inflammation, weight loss, and cough.

Desquamative interstitial pneumonia is a type of idiopathic interstitial pneumonia, which is characterized by the accumulation of bronchiolocentric alveolar macrophages in alveolar spaces and interstitial inflammation. This condition involves mild bronchiolar fibrosis and chronic inflammation. Moreover, desquamative interstitial pneumonia has exact synonyms such as RBILD, familial desquamative interstitial pneumonitis, and respiratory bronchiolitis-associated interstitial lung disease.

Lymphoid interstitial pneumonia is a type of idiopathic interstitial pneumonia, which is characterized by at least having symptoms such as cough. It is defined as an idiopathic interstitial pneumonia that involves diffuse interstitial infiltration of involved areas mostly with T lymphocytes, plasma cells, and macrophages. Lymphoid hyperplasia is frequently seen. The onset of this condition is often slow, with gradually increasing cough and breathlessness over a period of 3 or more years. Other occasional symptoms may include fever, weight loss, chest pain, and arthralgia. As the disease progresses, crackles may be detected.

Inhalation anthrax is a type of anthrax disease characterized by several symptoms, including tiredness, cough, low-grade fever, dyspnea (shortness of breath), chest discomfort, and pharynx inflammation. It is defined as an anthrax disease that results in infection located in lung lymph nodes, which is brought on by breathing in the spores of the bacteria Bacillus anthracis. The initial symptoms of inhalation anthrax resemble those of a cold or flu and can include a sore throat, mild fever, and muscle aches, with later symptoms expanding to cough, chest discomfort, shortness of breath, tiredness, and muscle aches. Inhalation anthrax is also known by exact synonyms such as pulmonary anthrax, respiratory anthrax, wool-sorters' disease, and woolsorters' disease.

Lower respiratory tract disease is the same as something that intersects between a disease and something that, at a minimum, has the location within the lower respiratory tract. It is a type of respiratory system disease and is defined as a respiratory system disease that involves the lower respiratory tract.

Tuberculous salpingitis is a type of fallopian tube disease and a type of urogenital tuberculosis. It is defined as an urogenital tuberculosis that results in the formation of granulomas located in the fallopian tube, signifying its classification as a condition that affects the fallopian tube.

Autoimmune polyendocrine syndrome type 1 is a type of autoimmune polyendocrine syndrome with a definition highlighting it as an autoimmune polyendocrine syndrome inherited in an autosomal recessive fashion, characterized by abnormal functioning of the immune system that causes auto-reactivity against endocrine organs. It is exactly synonymous with Autoimmune Polyglandular Syndrome I, Whitaker syndrome, and autoimmune polyendocrinopathy-candidiasis-ectodermal dystrophy.

Autoimmune polyendocrine syndrome type 2 is a specific type of autoimmune polyendocrine syndrome. It is defined as an autoimmune polyendocrine syndrome that is characterized by the abnormal functioning of the immune system, which causes auto-reactivity against endocrine organs. This condition is more heterogeneous and has not been linked to a single gene. Additionally, autoimmune polyendocrine syndrome type 2 is exactly synonymous with Schmidt syndrome.

Cutaneous lupus erythematosus is defined as a lupus erythematosus that causes skin lesions on parts of the body that are exposed to sunlight. It is a type of lupus erythematosus and also a type of skin disease. Moreover, it is equivalent to an intersection of conditions that are part of lupus erythematosus and diseases that have a location in some zone of the skin.

Kunjin encephalitis is a type of West Nile encephalitis. It is defined as a West Nile encephalitis that results in an infection located in the brain. This condition has a material basis in the Kunjin virus, which is a subtype of the West Nile Virus. It is transmitted by the bite of the Culex annulirostris mosquito. The symptoms of Kunjin encephalitis include fever, rigor, headache, confusion, and lethargy. This underlines the significance of the Kunjin virus and the role of Culex annulirostris in the transmission of this encephalitis, alongside its notable symptoms such as confusion, lethargy, headache, and fever.

Tick-borne encephalitis is a type of viral infectious disease that has a material basis in the Tick-borne encephalitis virus and is transmitted by Ixodes ticks. This disease results in inflammation located in the brain and is characterized by symptoms such as confusion, drowsiness, paralysis, and sensory disturbances. Additionally, tick-borne encephalitis is known by several exact synonyms, including Central European encephalitis, Far Eastern TBE, Russian spring-summer encephalitis, Siberian tick-borne encephalitis, Taiga encephalitis, Western European tick-borne encephalitis, and West-Siberian encephalitis.

A monogenic disease is defined as a genetic disease that results from one or more abnormal alleles and may be dominant, semi-dominant, or recessive. It is a type of genetic disease that is the same as a disease with a basis in at least one gene, representing the intersection of a disease and a condition that has a genetic basis.

Powassan encephalitis is a type of tick-borne encephalitis and a viral infectious disease that results in inflammation located in the brain. This condition has a material basis in the Powassan virus, which is transmitted by Ixodes and Dermacentor species of ticks. It is characterized by various symptoms including confusion, drowsiness, paralysis, seizures, tremors, stiff neck, headache, coma, fever, vomiting, sleepiness, breathing distress, and coma.

Erythema multiforme is a type of disease that is both allergic and skin-related, characterized by having symptoms that include allergic reactions. It is defined as a skin disease that is a type of allergic reaction located in the skin, occurring in response to medications, infections, or illness.

Nipah virus encephalitis is a type of viral infectious disease that is defined as a condition resulting in inflammation located in the brain, with its material basis in the Nipah virus. This disease is transmitted by direct contact with sick persons or animals, or through their contaminated tissues. It is characterized by several symptoms, including dizziness, drowsiness, altered consciousness, disorientation, and coma.

Argentine hemorrhagic fever is a type of viral infectious disease with a material basis in Junin virus, a member of the mammarenavirus family, specifically Juninense. It is transmitted by the rodent Calomys musculinus. The symptoms of Argentine hemorrhagic fever include fever, fatigue, malaise, thrombocytopenia (low platelet count), leukopenia (low white blood cell count), and hemorrhagic manifestations.

Bolivian hemorrhagic fever is a type of viral infectious disease that has its material basis in Mammarenavirus machupoense and is transmitted by the Calomys callosus, a type of vesper mouse. The symptoms of this disease include bleeding, joint pain, headache, fever, bronchopulmonary bleeding, gastrointestinal bleeding, and fatigue. Moreover, the definition of Bolivian hemorrhagic fever encompasses it being a hemorrhagic fever with a basis in Mammarenavirus machupoense, transmitted by Calomys callosus, and characterized by symptoms such as fever, headache, fatigue, myalgia, arthralgia, bleeding from the oral and nasal mucosa, as well as bleeding from the bronchopulmonary, gastrointestinal, and genitourinary tracts.

Venezuelan hemorrhagic fever is a viral infectious disease characterized by being a type of hemorrhagic fever. It has a material basis in Mammarenavirus guanaritoense. This disease is transmitted by the cotton rat, Sigmodon alstoni, or the cane mouse, Zygodontomys brevicauda. Venezuelan hemorrhagic fever presents with a range of symptoms including bleeding, weakness, melena, epistaxis, nausea, hepatomegaly, headache, anorexia, convulsion, fever, gum bleeding, menorrhagia, vomiting, hematemesis, and pharynx inflammation. Additionally, the definition of Venezuelan hemorrhagic fever outlines that the infection also has symptoms such as myalgia and sore throat, further emphasizing the wide array of symptoms associated with this condition.

Brazilian hemorrhagic fever is a viral infectious disease characterized as a type of hemorrhagic fever. It has a material basis in Mammarenavirus brazilense and is transmitted by rodents. The symptoms of Brazilian hemorrhagic fever include fever, bleeding, bloodshot eyes, dizziness, fatigue, muscle aches, loss of strength, and bleeding under the skin, internal organs, or from body orifices such as the mouth, eyes, or ears.

Chapare hemorrhagic fever is a type of viral infectious disease that is defined as a hemorrhagic fever with a material basis in Mammarenavirus chapareense. This infection manifests through several symptoms, including headache, joint pain, muscle pain, vomiting, shock, and bleeding.

Whitewater Arroyo hemorrhagic fever is defined as a viral infectious disease categorized as a hemorrhagic fever. It has its material basis in the Mammarenavirus whitewaterense and is transmitted by white-throated woodrats (Neotoma albigula). The disease is characterized by symptoms including fever, headache, myalgia, and hemorrhagic manifestations.

Korean hemorrhagic fever, a type of hantavirus hemorrhagic fever with renal syndrome, is transmitted by both the Eurasian field mouse, Apodemus agrarius, and the Norwegian rat, Rattus norvegicus. It is characterized by a wide range of symptoms including backache, hypotension, bloodshot eyes, shock, abdominal pain, nausea, rash, headache, flushing, fever, low blood pressure, and chills. Korean hemorrhagic fever is defined as a hemorrhagic fever with renal syndrome that results in an infection located in the kidney, caused by the Hantaan virus or the Seoul virus. The infection's symptoms also encompass headache, back pain, abdominal pain, fever, chills, nausea, blurred vision, flushing of the face, redness of the eyes, rash, low blood pressure, acute shock, vascular leakage, and acute kidney failure, which can lead to severe fluid overload.

Nephropathia epidemica is a type of hantavirus hemorrhagic fever with renal syndrome. It is defined as a hemorrhagic fever that results in an infection located in the kidney. This condition has a material basis in the Orthohantavirus Puumalaense, which is at least transmitted by the bank vole, Myodes glareolus. The symptoms of Nephropathia epidemica include headache, nausea, backache, vomiting, myalgia, abdominal pain, internal hemorrhage, and renal failure.

Lujo hemorrhagic fever is a type of viral infectious disease and is also a type of condition that at least has the symptom of some bleeding. It is defined as a viral infectious disease that results in infection, has a material basis in Lujo virus, and has the symptom of bleeding.

Epstein Barr virus hepatitis is a type of viral hepatitis and also a type of Epstein Barr virus infectious disease. It is characterized by having a material basis in Human gammaherpesvirus 4 and manifests various symptoms, including liver inflammation, abdominal pain, nausea, headache, jaundice, fever, and fatigue. This condition specifically results in inflammation located in the liver, caused by Human herpesvirus 4, and is associated with symptoms such as headache, fatigue, fever, abdominal pain, nausea, and jaundice.

Swine influenza is a type of influenza that has a material basis in either the Influenza A virus or the Influenza C virus, encompassing subtypes such as H1N1, H1N2, H3N1, H3N2, and H2N3. These viruses can infect both pigs and humans, transmitted through direct contact with infected pigs. Swine influenza is characterized by a range of symptoms including lethargy, rhinorrhea (runny nose), nausea, diarrhea, fever, cough, vomiting, and pharynx inflammation (sore throat). Additionally, the infection may result in a lack of appetite and coughing in humans.

Lambert Eaton Myasthenic Syndrome (LEMS) is identified as a type of autoimmune disease affecting both the musculoskeletal and peripheral nervous systems. It is also categorized as a neuromuscular junction disease and is known to have a phenotype involving abnormal immunoglobulin levels. The disease is defined by a disruption in acetylcholine (ACh) release at the neuromuscular junction, which is attributed to an autoimmune response against voltage-gated calcium channels (VGCC) on the presynaptic motor nerve terminal. Additionally, Lambert Eaton Myasthenic Syndrome is precisely referred to by several exact synonyms, including Eaton-Lambert Syndrome and Lambert-Eaton Syndrome.

Polycystic echinococcosis is a type of echinococcosis and a type of liver disease, specifically an echinococcosis that infects the liver. This condition is caused by the larvae of Echinococcus vogeli or Echinococcus oligarthrus. Moreover, polycystic echinococcosis is also known by its exact synonyms: human polycystic hydatid disease and neotropical echinococcosis.

Selective IgM deficiency disease is a type of dysgammaglobulinemia and is defined as a selective immunoglobulin deficiency disease. It results from decreased levels of immunoglobulin M (IgM) production compared to the production of other antibodies.

Primary amebic meningoencephalitis is defined as a parasitic protozoa infectious disease that involves the infection of the central nervous system caused by Naegleria fowleri, which is exactly synonymous with Naegleria fowleri infection. This disease represents an intersection of parasitic protozoan infectious diseases and central nervous system diseases, characterized by several symptoms including delirium, seizures, nausea, headache, coma, and vomiting.

Granulomatous amebic encephalitis (GAE) is a type of primary amebic meningoencephalitis and brain disease characterized by symptoms such as headache and altered mental status. This condition specifically affects the brain. It is defined as a parasitic protozoa infectious disease resulting in brain infection caused by Acanthamoeba or Balamuthia mandrillaris, with symptoms that include headaches, altered mental status, and focal neurologic deficit. These symptoms progress over several weeks, eventually leading to death. The disease is also known by several exact synonyms, including Acanthamoeba encephalitis, Acanthamoeba granulomatous encephalitis, Granulomatous Amebic Encephalitis due to Acanthamoeba, and granulomatous amoebic encephalitis.

Philophthalmiasis is a type of eye disease and a form of parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease that specifically affects the eyes. It is characterized as a parasitic infection of the eyes by Philophthalmus species. The disease manifests in two forms: external ocular philophthalmiasis, which presents as follicular conjunctivitis and superficial keratitis, and sub-conjunctival ocular philophthalmiasis, which involves mild edema with minimal cellular reaction.

Coenurosis is a parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease that is classified as both a central nervous system disease and a skin disease. It is also characterized by its symptoms, which include vomiting. Furthermore, coenurosis is defined as a parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease resulting from the infection by the metacestode larval stage (coenurus) of Taenia multiceps or Taenia serialis. This disease manifests in various ways depending on its location: when coenuri are in the skin or subcutaneous tissue, they appear as painless nodules located on the trunk, sclera, subconjunctiva, neck, shoulders, head, and limbs. When coenuri affect the central nervous system, symptoms can include headache, fever, vomiting, nerve palsies, jacksonian epilepsy, pachymeningitis, obstructive or communicating hydrocephalus, and intracranial arteritis with transient hemiparesis. In the eye, coenuri cause both intraocular and orbital infections.

Mesocestoidiasis is a type of parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease that involves a parasitic cestode infection caused by Mesocestoides lineatus, resulting in symptoms such as nausea, diarrhea, abdominal discomfort, and vomiting.

Acanthocephaliasis is a type of parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease that involves infection of the intestine caused by thorny-headed worms, specifically Macracanthorhynchus or Moniliformis moniliformis. This disease presents with several symptoms, including abdominal distention, weight loss, bloody stool, decreased appetite, abdominal pain, nausea, diarrhea, fever, vomiting, and constipation.

Angiostrongyliasis is a type of disease that affects various parts of the body, including the central nervous system, intestines, and eyes. It is categorized as a parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease, which means it is caused by parasitic worms, specifically by Angiostrongylus cantonensis or Angiostrongylus costaricensis. This disease is defined by its ability to cause parasitic infection in the intestine, central nervous system, and eyes. Moreover, angiostrongyliasis has a material basis in the angiostrongylus species, indicating that these specific parasites are responsible for the infection.

Baylisascariasis is a type of parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease, which is a comprehensive category that encompasses various specific types including spinal cord disease, intestinal disease, eye disease, and brain disease. This disease is characterized by its ability to affect multiple bodily locations, intersecting the domains of diseases that have their location in the intestine, brain, eye, and spinal cord. Additionally, baylisascariasis is associated with at least one symptom, namely blindness. The definition of baylisascariasis elaborates on its nature as a parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease that involves a parasitic infection of the intestine caused by the larvae of Baylisascaris procyonis. This infection has the potential to invade the spinal cord, brain, and eye of humans, leading to severe outcomes such as permanent neurological damage, blindness, or even death.

Dioctophymiasis is a type of disease characterized by its impact on both the skin and the kidneys, as well as being a specific form of parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease. It is defined as a parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease that involves a parasitic infection by the nematode Dioctophyme renale in humans, which occurs after consuming undercooked food. The infection manifests with larvae found in subcutaneous nodules and the kidneys, highlighting its dual nature of affecting both the skin and the kidneys.

Thelaziasis is a type of parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease defined as a condition that results from the infection of the eyes in humans by the nematode Thelazia callipaeda. This disease leads to varying degrees of inflammation and lacrimation. In more severe cases of infection, individuals may experience photophobia, edema, conjunctivitis, and even blindness.

Tungiasis is a type of parasitic ectoparasitic infectious disease that has symptoms including skin lesions and itching. It is defined as an inflammatory skin disease caused by the parasitic infestation of the female chigoe flea, Tunga penetrans, in animals and humans. The symptoms of tungiasis include skin inflammation, severe pain, itching, and a lesion at the site of infection. This lesion is characterized by a black dot at the center of a swollen red lesion, surrounded by a white halo.

Ophthalmomyiasis is a type of myiasis and an eye disease, characterized by its occurrence in the eye, where at least some diseases are located. It is defined as a myiasis that involves the parasitic infestation of Oestrus ovis larvae in the eye, causing severe irritation, edema, and pain.

Trichomonas vaginalis trichomoniasis is a type of disease that encompasses several conditions affecting the urogenital tract, specifically characterized as a vaginal, vulvar, cervix, and urethral disease. This condition is also known by its exact synonym, urogenital trichomonas. It is classified as a subtype of trichomoniasis, which is caused by the Trichomonas vaginalis organism. This particular disease is notable for intersecting with diseases located in the uterine cervix, urethra, vagina, and mammalian vulva. The transmission of Trichomonas vaginalis trichomoniasis occurs through contact, specifically sexual contact. Symptoms associated with this disease include headache and relapsing fever, in addition to inflammation of the cervix, urethra, and vagina, which may result in an itching or burning sensation alongside yellow-green, itchy, frothy, and foul-smelling vaginal discharge. The comprehensive definition of Trichomonas vaginalis trichomoniasis highlights its nature as an infection of the urogenital tract, with its material basis in Trichomonas vaginalis, and details the transmission method and symptoms experienced by affected individuals.

Trichomonas tenax trichomoniasis is a specific form of trichomoniasis that manifests as a mouth disease, characterized by its basis in the protozoan parasite Trichomonas tenax. This condition is transmitted through droplet spread and vehicle-borne fomite transmission mechanisms. It is primarily located in the oral cavity. The disease is defined as a trichomoniasis caused by the single-celled protozoan parasite Trichomonas tenax, which is transmitted through oral droplets, by kissing, or via fomites such as eating utensils. This particular strain of trichomoniasis leads to periodontitis and bronchopulmonary trichomoniasis through aspiration from the oropharynx.

Basidiobolomycosis is a type of subcutaneous mycosis defined as a chronic inflammatory or granulomatous fungal infection of the subcutaneous tissue of the limbs, chest, back, or buttocks caused by Basidiobolus ranarum. This condition is characterized by lesions that appear as subcutaneous nodules, which develop into massive, firm, indurated, painless swellings. These swellings are freely movable over the underlying muscle but are attached to the skin, which may become hyperpigmented but not ulcerated.

Conidiobolomycosis is a type of subcutaneous mycosis and is defined as a chronic inflammatory or granulomatous fungal infection caused by Conidiobolus species. It is restricted to the nasal submucosa and characterized by polyps or palpable restricted subcutaneous masses. The symptoms of this condition include nasal obstruction, drainage, and sinus pain, with subcutaneous nodules developing in the nasal and perinasal regions.

Penicilliosis is a type of opportunistic mycosis that primarily has its material basis in Talaromyces marneffei. It is characterized by various symptoms, including hepatosplenomegaly, skin lesions, weight loss, anemia, and fever. The definition of penicilliosis outlines it as an opportunistic mycosis resulting from Penicillium marneffei, leading to a systemic infection. This infection manifests through symptoms such as fever, anemia, weight loss, lymphadenopathy, hepatosplenomegaly, respiratory signs, and skin lesions.

Fusariosis is an opportunistic mycosis and a type of condition that involves at least some necrosis as a symptom. It is defined as an opportunistic mycosis that involves localized or hematogenously disseminated fungal infection by Fusarium solani or Fusarium oxysporum. In neutropenic patients, skin lesions are observed, and in immunocompromised patients, indolent cellulitis or soft-tissue necrosis occurs at the site of trauma.

Trichosporonosis is a type of opportunistic mycosis and also a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some Trichosporon. It is defined as an opportunistic mycosis that results in disseminated infection, has a material basis in Trichosporon, and results in the formation of nontender erythematous nodules anywhere on the body.

Parasitic ichthyosporea infectious disease is a type of parasitic infectious disease that is defined by a parasitic infection involving members of the class Ichthyosporea, which are parasites of fish and other animals.

Primary systemic mycosis is a type of systemic mycosis and is also a type of condition that has a material basis in some fungi. It is defined as a systemic mycosis that results in an infection located in the human body, has a material basis in Fungi, and can overcome the physiological and cellular defenses of the normal human host. The primary deep pathogens usually gain access to the host via the respiratory tract.
Aniseikonia is a type of refractive error, defined as a refractive error that is characterized by a significant difference in the perceived sizes of an object between the two eyes.

Alkhurma hemorrhagic fever is a type of Kyasanur Forest disease and is defined as a viral infectious disease that is categorized under hemorrhagic fevers. It has its material basis in the Alkhurma hemorrhagic fever virus. The disease is transmitted by the Ornithodoros savignyi tick bite, ingestion of unpasteurized camel milk, or entry via skin wounds. Alkhurma hemorrhagic fever is characterized by several symptoms, including headache, joint pain, muscle pain, vomiting, thrombocytopenia, and hemorrhagic fever.

Congenital hypothyroidism is a type of physical disorder and a specific form of hypothyroidism, which is a disease rooted in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a hypothyroidism that is present at birth.

Lacrimoauriculodentodigital syndrome 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, also known as LADD syndrome, and is a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. This syndrome is defined by a syndrome that arises from a heterozygous mutation in the tyrosine kinase domain of the FGFR2 gene located on chromosome 10q26. It is characterized by the autosomal dominant inheritance of abnormalities affecting the lacrimal and salivary glands and ducts, ears, teeth, and fingers and toes. Lacrimoauriculodentodigital syndrome 1 is also precisely referred to as LEVY-HOLLISTER SYNDROME, Lacrimo-auriculo-dento-digital syndrome 1, and lacrimoauriculodentodigital syndrome, signifying its exact synonyms.

An enlarged vestibular aqueduct is defined as a vestibular disease characterized by progressive hearing loss resulting from congenital enlargement of the vestibular aqueducts. It is considered the same as an entity that intersects with a condition at the junction of vestibular disease and any disease located at least in the vestibular aqueduct. Moreover, an enlarged vestibular aqueduct is classified as a type of vestibular disease.

Bradyopsia is a type of autosomal recessive and retinal disease, which at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a retinal disease characterized by the slower than usual adaptation of the eyes to changing light conditions. Additionally, bradyopsia is exactly synonymous with prolonged electroretinal response suppression.

Hypophosphatemia is a type of phosphorus metabolism disease and is characterized by hypophosphatemia. It has symptoms such as bone pain and features diseases like osteoarthritis. Additionally, it is defined as a phosphorus metabolism disease characterized by hypophosphatemia with the symptoms of osteomalacia, including bone pain, skeletal deformities, and osteoarthritis.

Primary bacterial infectious disease is a type of bacterial infectious disease. It is defined as a bacterial infectious disease that results from infection by bacteria due to their presence or activity within a normal, healthy host. The intrinsic virulence of the bacteria is, in part, a necessary consequence of their need to reproduce and spread.

Commensal bacterial infectious disease is a type of bacterial infectious disease. It is defined as a bacterial infectious disease that results in an infection by bacteria which are part of the normal human flora. This occurs when one or more of the defense mechanisms designed to restrict these bacteria from the usually sterile internal tissues are breached, whether by accident, by intent (such as surgery), or by an underlying metabolic or infectious disorder.

Opportunistic bacterial infectious disease is a type of bacterial infectious disease that is defined as a bacterial infectious disease resulting in infection by bacteria in individuals whose host defense mechanisms have been compromised.

Foodborne botulism is a type of botulism that involves intoxication caused by botulinum neurotoxins (BoNTA, B, E, and F), which are transmitted by ingestion of food contaminated with preformed toxins. It has a material basis in Clostridium botulinum A, Clostridium botulinum B, Clostridium botulinum E, and Clostridium botulinum F. This type of botulism is transmitted through vehicle-borne ingestion. It is characterized by symptoms such as double vision, dysarthria, dysphagia, dysphonia, descending muscle paralysis, blurred vision, and diplopia.

Wound botulism is a type of botulism and also a type of condition that is transmitted by some form of contact transmission. It is defined as a botulism that involves intoxication caused by botulinum neurotoxins (BoNTA, B, E, and F). These neurotoxins have a material basis in Clostridium botulinum A, Clostridium botulinum B, Clostridium botulinum E, and Clostridium botulinum F. The transmission occurs through the contact of spores with open wounds, which then reproduce in an anaerobic environment to produce toxins.

Infant botulism is a type of botulism that can be transmitted through vehicle-borne ingestion. It is characterized by symptoms such as lethargy, muscle weakness, ptosis, dysphagia, and constipation. Specifically, infant botulism involves intoxication caused by botulinum neurotoxins (BoNTA or B), originating from Clostridium botulinum A or Clostridium botulinum B. These bacteria are transmitted by the ingestion of bacterial spores, which then proliferate in the intestine and release toxins. The infection manifests with symptoms including constipation, lethargy, difficulty feeding, difficulties with swallowing, ptosis, loss of head control, and muscle weakness.
Glandular tularemia is a type of tularemia, defined as a tularemia that results in the swelling of regional lymph glands.

Typhoidal tularemia is a type of tularemia, which is a type of condition that at least has symptoms including weight loss, fever, chills, and malaise. Typhoidal tularemia is defined as a tularemia that results in bacteremia and is characterized by symptoms such as fever, chills, myalgia, malaise, and weight loss.
Nonpapillary renal cell carcinoma is a type of hereditary renal cell carcinoma defined by a hereditary renal cell carcinoma that has a material basis in a loss of 3p13-pter sequences.

Carrion's disease is a type of bartonellosis and something that at least has a material basis in some Bartonella bacilliformis. It is defined as a bartonellosis that results in infection located in endothelial cells or red blood cells, caused by Bartonella bacilliformis, which is transmitted by sandflies of the genus Lutzomyia. The infection has both acute and chronic phases. The acute phase is characterized by severe hemolytic anemia and transient immunosuppression, while the chronic phase is characterized by verruga peruana lesions, which may ulcerate and bleed. Additionally, Carrion's disease has exact synonyms: Carrion disease and Oroya fever.

Complement Factor I deficiency is a type of complement deficiency that is defined as a complement deficiency characterized by recurrent pyogenic bacterial infections due to a deficiency in complement component 3. It has exact synonyms including C3 INACTIVATOR DEFICIENCY and COMPLEMENT COMPONENT 3 INACTIVATOR DEFICIENCY.

Familial adenomatous polyposis is a type of autosomal genetic disease and also an intestinal disease, which is characterized by a material basis in autosomal inheritance. It is defined as an intestinal disease that involves the formation of numerous polyps in the epithelium of the large intestine due to mutations in the APC gene; these polyps are initially benign but later can transform into colon cancer. Familial adenomatous polyposis is also exactly synonymous with adenomatous polyposis of the colon.

Restless legs syndrome is a type of central nervous system disease characterized by throbbing, pulling, creeping, or other unpleasant sensations in the legs and the irresistible urge to move them. It is also known by its exact synonyms: WED, Willis-Ekbom disease, and Wittmaack-Ekbom syndrome.

Stevens-Johnson Syndrome is a type of skin disease characterized by the ulceration of less than 10% of the body's surface area. This disease is often triggered by the use of medications, such as antibiotics or antiepileptics, or the onset of an infection. Moreover, Stevens-Johnson Syndrome has an exact match with the MESH identifier D013262.

Xeroderma pigmentosum is a syndrome and a type of autosomal recessive disease, which at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by a deficiency in the ability to repair ultraviolet damage, which has a material basis in the autosomal recessive inheritance of DNA repair.

Nonepidermolytic palmoplantar keratoderma is a type of palmoplantar keratosis and is characterized by a well-demarcated, symmetric keratoderma that is located in both the palms and soles. It is also known by its exact synonyms: Thost-Unna Syndrome, Unna-Thost Syndrome, diffuse nonepidermolytic palmoplantar keratoderma, and tylosis.

Hailey-Hailey disease is an autosomal dominant disease and a type of pemphigus, specifically characterized by recurring blistering, most commonly in the skin folds. This condition arises due to mutations in the ATP2C1 gene, leading to a loss of adhesion within the skin. It is also known by its exact synonyms, BENIGN CHRONIC PEMPHIGUS and Pemphigus, Benign Familial. Furthermore, it is associated with a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Multiple endocrine neoplasia type 2a (MEN2A) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of multiple endocrine neoplasia that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by medullary carcinoma of the thyroid, pheochromocytoma, hyperparathyroidism, and occasionally cutaneous lichen amyloidosis. MEN2A is also known by its exact synonyms: Sipple syndrome and multiple endocrine neoplasia II.

Arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardiomyopathy is a type of intrinsic cardiomyopathy characterized by hypokinetic areas involving the free wall of the right ventricle, with fibrofatty replacement of the right ventricular myocardium. This condition is associated with arrhythmias originating in the right ventricle and limited or no involvement of the left ventricle. It has several exact synonyms, including ARVC, ARVC cardiomyopathy, ARVD, arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardiomyopathy, arrhythmogenic right ventricular dysplasia, arrhythmogenic right ventricular dysplasia/cardiomyopathy, and right ventricular ACM.

Asperger syndrome is a type of autism spectrum disorder characterized by significant difficulties in social interaction, along with restricted and repetitive patterns of behavior and interests. It is distinguished from other autism spectrum disorders by its relative preservation of linguistic and cognitive development.

Fatal familial insomnia is a type of prion disease that is characterized by insomnia, hallucinations, dementia, and death, located in the brain. This disease also falls under the category of conditions that at least have the symptom of some hallucination.

Andersen Tawil Syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and also falls under the category of Long QT Syndrome. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and presents symptoms such as arrhythmia. This condition is defined as a Long QT syndrome that results from an autosomal dominant inheritance of a mutation in the KCNJ2 gene, which disrupts the rhythm of the heart's lower chambers (ventricular arrhythmia) and leads to an unusually small lower jaw (micrognathia), low-set ears, and an abnormal curvature of the fingers known as clinodactyly. Andersen Tawil Syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms, including Andersen Cardiodysrhythmic Periodic Paralysis, Andersen Syndrome, LQT7, Long QT Syndrome 7, and Potassium-Sensitive Cardiodysrhythmic Type.

Mulibrey nanism is a type of autosomal recessive disease and syndrome, which specifically has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by global growth retardation of the muscle, liver, brain, and eyes, as well as constrictive pericarditis, and is caused by mutations in the TRIM37 gene. Mulibrey nanism is also known by several exact synonyms, including MUL, Mulibrey growth disorder, Muscle-Liver-Brain-Eye Nanism, PERICARDIAL CONSTRICTION AND GROWTH FAILURE, and Perheentupa Syndrome.

Danon disease is a type of X-linked dominant disease and also falls under the category of lysosomal storage diseases. It is characterized by a material basis in some X-linked dominant inheritance. Danon disease is defined as a lysosomal storage disease that is characterized by cardiomyopathy, skeletal myopathy, and intellectual disability, with its material basis in mutations in the LAMP2 gene. Furthermore, Danon disease is exactly synonymous with Antopol Disease and also known as Pseudoglycogenosis II.

Frasier syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease, which at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by gonadal dysgenesis, streak gonads, progressive focal segmental glomerulonephropathy, and the development of urogenital cancers, resulting from a mutation in the WT1 gene.

Usher syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease, which means it at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by a combination of hearing loss and visual impairment.

Familial partial lipodystrophy is a type of partial lipodystrophy characterized by abnormal subcutaneous adipose tissue distribution beginning in late childhood or early adult life. It is also known by its exact synonyms, Dunnigan Syndrome and Koberling-Dunnigan Syndrome.

Mucosulfatidosis is a type of autosomal recessive disease, sphingolipidosis, and something that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by leukodystrophy, ichthyosis, skeletal abnormalities, and shortened life expectancy due to a mutation in the SUMF1 gene, which results in a deficiency in multiple sulfatase enzymes. Additionally, mucosulfatidosis is exactly synonymous with Sulfatidosis, Juvenile, Austin Type, and multiple sulfatase deficiency disease.

Infantile Refsum disease is a type of peroxisomal disease and can also be referred to as infantile phytanic acid storage disease. It is characterized by neurological impairment, intellectual disability, hepatosplenomegaly, and ichthyosis. This condition results from the accumulation of very long chain fatty acids and phytanic acid, secondary to mutations in the PEX genes. Furthermore, infantile Refsum disease is associated with symptoms including, at least, some hepatosplenomegaly.

X-linked dominant hypophosphatemic rickets is a type of rickets and a type of X-linked dominant disease. It is also classified as a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of X-linked dominant inheritance. This condition is defined as a form of rickets that has its material basis in X-linked mutations in the PHEX gene. These mutations lead to increased circulating levels of FGF-23, a phosphate-regulating hormone (phosphatonin), which results in reduced renal phosphate reabsorption and, consequently, abnormal bone mineralization. Additionally, X-linked dominant hypophosphatemic rickets is known by several exact synonyms, including Hypophosphatemia, Vitamin D-Resistant Rickets; Vitamin D-Resistant Rickets, X-Linked; X-linked hypophosphatemia; and hypophosphatemic rickets X-linked dominant.

White sponge nevus is a type of skin disease, which is characterized by a defect in the normal process of keratinization of the mucosa. It is also known by its exact synonyms, hereditary mucosal leukokeratosis and white sponge nevus of Cannon.

Pachyonychia congenita is a type of autosomal dominant disease and syndrome, which essentially has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by hypertrophic nails and hyperkeratosis of the hands and feet, stemming from gene mutations that lead to changes in keratin. Furthermore, Pachyonychia congenita is also known by its exact synonyms: Jackson-Lawler Type Pachyonychia Congenita, Jadassohn-Lewandowsky Syndrome, PACHYONYCHIA CONGENITA, JADASSOHN-LEWANDOWSKY TYPE, and Pachyonychia Congenita Type 1.

Gitelman syndrome is a type of disease that falls under the categories of autosomal recessive disease, renal tubular transport disease, and has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a renal tubular transport disease characterized by mutations in genes producing proteins essential for the kidneys' reabsorption of salt (sodium chloride or NaCl) from urine back into the bloodstream. This condition impairs the kidneys' ability to reabsorb salt, leading to the loss of excess salt in the urine, known as salt wasting. Furthermore, Gitelman syndrome is exactly synonymous with HYPOMAGNESEMIA-HYPOKALEMIA, PRIMARY RENOTUBULAR, WITH HYPOCALCIURIA.

Brugada syndrome is a type of monogenic disease, heart conduction disease, and something that has its basis in at least one gene. It is defined as a heart conduction disease characterized by abnormal electrocardiogram (ECG) findings and an increased risk of sudden cardiac death. Brugada syndrome has several exact synonyms, including Bangungut, Brugada type idiopathic ventricular fibrillation, Dream disease, Pokkuri death syndrome, SUNDS, and sudden unexplained nocturnal death syndrome.

Mevalonic aciduria is a type of peroxisomal disease and is also a type of condition that has its basis in some structural variant. It is defined as a peroxisomal disease characterized by cortical atrophy, microcephaly, dysmorphic facies, muscular hypotonia, and intellectual disability. This condition has a material basis in a mutation in the MVK gene, which results in a deficiency of mevalonate kinase and impaired cholesterol biosynthesis. Moreover, mevalonic aciduria has the exact synonym "Mevalonate Kinase Deficiency."

Lissencephaly is a congenital nervous system abnormality that is a type of disease located in the cerebral cortex. It is characterized by the absence of folds in the cerebral cortex, which is caused by defective neuronal migration during the 12th to 24th weeks of gestation.

Periventricular nodular heterotopia is a type of congenital nervous system abnormality which is characterized by the improper migration of neurons during the early development of the fetal brain. It is also exactly synonymous with periventricular heterotopia.

Buruli ulcer disease is a primary bacterial infectious disease with a material basis in Mycobacterium ulcerans, transmitted by vector borne transmission. It is characterized by symptoms such as skin lesions and necrosis. The disease results in infection located in the skin or subcutaneous tissue, transmitted by insects, and involves the production of a toxin named mycolactone by the bacterium. This toxin causes subcutaneous fat necrosis and inhibits an immune response, leading to a nodule symptom, which is a painless, mobile swelling in the skin. Additionally, Buruli ulcer disease is also known by several exact synonyms including Bairnsdale ulcer, Daintree ulcer, Mossman ulcer, Searl ulcer, and Searle's ulcer.

Sertoli cell only syndrome is a type of male infertility and has the exact synonyms DEL CASTILLO SYNDROME and Germinal Cell Aplasia. It is defined as a male infertility disease characterized by male sterility, with a material basis in azospermia without abnormal sexual development.

Juvenile myelomonocytic leukemia is a type of myelodysplastic/myeloproliferative neoplasm, which is also categorized as something that typically begins during young adulthood. It is defined as a myelodysplastic/myeloproliferative neoplasm characterized by the uncontrolled growth of monocytes.

Hyperphosphatemia is a type of phosphorus metabolism disease characterized by elevated levels of phosphorus in the blood and abnormal deposits of phosphate and calcium in joints and soft tissues. This condition results from abnormal phosphorus metabolism and has a material basis in mutations in the FGF23, GALNT3, or KL gene.

Wolf Hirschhorn Syndrome is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome characterized by distinct craniofacial features, hypotonia, and intellectual disability. It has a material basis in a hemizygous deletion of chromosome 4p16.3. This condition is also precisely known by several synonyms, including 4p deletion syndrome, PITT SYNDROME, Pitt-Rogers-Danks Syndrome, and chromosome 4p16.3 deletion syndrome.

Aspartylglucosaminuria, also known precisely as aspartylglucosaminidase deficiency, aspartylglycosaminuria, and glycosylasparaginase deficiency, is a type of lysosomal storage disease and falls under diseases that have their basis in some structural variant. It is characterized by delayed speech beginning at 2-3 years of age. This condition occurs due to mutations in the AGA gene, which lead to the absence or shortage of the aspartylglucosaminidase enzyme in lysosomes. This enzyme deficiency prevents the normal breakdown of glycoproteins. Aspartylglucosaminuria is exactly matched with the MESH identifier D054880.

Antley Bixler Syndrome with disordered steroidogenesis is a type of syndrome, which is a specific form of Antley Bixler Syndrome and is considered an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a condition that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is associated with symptoms that diseases typically have. Specifically, this syndrome is defined as an Antley-Bixler Syndrome characterized at birth or prenatally by malformations and deformities affecting the majority of the skeleton and other areas of the body, with autosomal recessive inheritance of the FGFR2 gene. It also has the exact synonym "trapezoidocephaly-synostosis syndrome" and an exact match with the MESH identifier D054882.

Campomelic dysplasia is a type of autosomal dominant disease and osteochondrodysplasia that at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an osteochondrodysplasia characterized by congenital shortness and bowing of long tubular bones, especially in the lower extremities, hypoplastic scapulae, narrow iliac wings, and nonmineralized thoracic pedicles due to a heterozygous mutation in the SOX9 gene on chromosome 17q24. Additionally, campomelic dysplasia has an exact synonym, Acampomelic Campomelic Dysplasia.

Farber lipogranulomatosis is a type of lipid storage disease characterized by abnormalities in swallowing, cognition, joint function, and the central nervous system. These abnormalities are due to a deficiency in the enzyme ceramidase that results in the deposition of sphingolipids. Farber lipogranulomatosis is also known by its exact synonyms: Farber disease, N-laurylsphingosine deacylase deficiency, and acid ceramidase deficiency.

Muir Torre syndrome is a type of Lynch syndrome and is characterized by a propensity to develop cancers of the gastrointestinal tract, genitourinary tract, and skin. This syndrome has a material basis in mutations in DNA mismatch repair genes.

Loeys-Dietz syndrome is a type of syndrome that is classified as an autosomal dominant disease, and it is based on autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by an increased risk of aortic aneurysm and dissection, elongated limbs, hypertelorism, bifid uvula, and easy skin bruising, which are due to mutations in TGFB3 that result in connective tissue defects.

Erythrokeratodermia variabilis is a type of monogenic disease, skin disease, and represents a condition with a genetic basis. It is defined as a skin disease characterized by areas of sharply demarcated, brown hyperkeratosis, which has a material basis in mutations in genes encoding for connexin channel proteins in the epidermis. Erythrokeratodermia variabilis is also known by its exact synonyms, Erythrokeratodermia Figurata Variabilis and Greither Disease, and has an exact match with the MESH identifier D056266.

Yellow nail syndrome is a type of syndrome, skin disease, and nail disease. It is situated at the intersection of conditions that have a location in some zone of the skin and conditions that have a location in the nails. Yellow nail syndrome is defined as a syndrome characterized by an accumulation of protein-rich fluid (lymph) in the soft layers of tissue under the skin resulting in pleural effusions, lymphedema (due to lymphatic hypoplasia), and yellow dystrophic nails that lack a cuticle, grow slowly, and are loose or detached.

Costello syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of RASopathy, which is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a RASopathy characterized by craniofacial dysmorphology, cardiac defects, mild mental retardation, and high birth weight followed by a failure to thrive and developmental delays. Additionally, Costello syndrome has exact synonyms, including FCS SYNDROME and Faciocutaneoskeletal Syndrome.

Donohue syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease, which at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by protuberant and low-set ears, flaring nostrils, thick lips, enlarged secondary sex organs, and overwhelming insulin resistance, with its material basis in mutations within the INSR gene causing abnormalities in the insulin receptor. Moreover, Donohue syndrome has the exact synonym Leprechaunism.

Carney Complex is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a syndrome that has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by myxomas, spotty pigmentation of the skin, and endocrine overactivity. Carney Complex is also exactly synonymous with Carney Complex, Type 1, Carney Complex, Type 2, Carney Syndrome, Carney complex variant, LAMB Syndrome, and NAME Syndrome.

Monilethrix is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of hair disease, characterized by something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a hair disease that is characterized by short, easily broken hair that results in alopecia and has a material basis in mutations in genes for type II hair cortex keratins.

Alstrom syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is characterized by multiorgan dysfunction. Key features of Alstrom syndrome include childhood obesity, blindness due to congenital retinal dystrophy, sensorineural hearing loss, and it has a material basis in mutations in the ALMS1 gene. Moreover, Alstrom syndrome has an exact match with MESH:D056769 and includes symptoms such as blindness.

Netherton syndrome is identified as a type of autosomal recessive disease and a form of skin disease, which fundamentally has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and exhibits symptoms including inflammation. It is defined as a skin disease characterized by chronic skin inflammation, trichorrhexis invaginata, atopic dermatitis, and is caused by mutations in the SPINK5 gene, leading to a reduced capacity to inhibit serine proteases expressed in the skin.

Weill Marchesani Syndrome is a type of syndrome, autosomal genetic disease, and something that at least has a material basis in autosomal inheritance. It is characterized by a syndrome with short stature, brachycephaly and other facial abnormalities, brachydactyly, joint stiffness, and distinctive ocular abnormalities. Furthermore, Weill Marchesani Syndrome is exactly synonymous with GEMSS syndrome, Marchesani-Weill Syndrome, Mesodermal Dysmorphodystrophy, Congenital, Spherophakia Brachymorphia Syndrome, and congenital mesodermal dystrophy.

Barth syndrome is a type of 3 methylglutaconic aciduria, and it is also known as a type of X-linked recessive disease. It is described as having a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. The definition of Barth syndrome is a 3-methylglutaconic aciduria that has a material basis in X-linked inheritance of the tafazzin gene, characterized by decreased production of an enzyme required to produce cardiolipin. Barth syndrome is exactly synonymous with 3-methylglutaconicaciduria type 2, 3-methylglutaconicaciduria type II, MGA Type 2, and MGA type II. Additionally, Barth syndrome has an exact match with MESH:D056889.

Liddle syndrome is a type of renal tubular transport disease and is defined as a renal tubular transport disease characterized by hypertension and hypokalemia caused by dysregulation of epithelial sodium channels, leading to overexpression of the channel. Furthermore, Liddle syndrome is exactly synonymous with Liddle's syndrome and Pseudoaldosteronism.

Epidemic typhus, which is also known precisely as sylvatic typhus, is a type of typhus caused by Rickettsia prowazekii and is characterized by several symptoms, including delirium, photophobia (sensitivity to light), stupor, rash, cough, high fever, and chills. This disease is transmitted by the human body louse, Pediculus humanus corporis, and through insect-borne transmission. The detailed definition of epidemic typhus elucidates that it is a typhus that materializes from the infection by Rickettsia prowazekii, conveyed by the human body louse. The infection manifests through symptoms like high fever, cough, rash, severe muscle pain, chills, falling blood pressure, stupor, sensitivity to light, and delirium.

Endemic typhus is a type of typhus that has a material basis in Rickettsia typhi or Rickettsia felis, which are transmitted by fleas, specifically Xenopsylla cheopis, through flea-borne transmission. The infection is characterized by symptoms such as headache, fever, chills, nausea, rash, cough, vomiting, and possibly myalgia. Endemic typhus is also known by several exact synonyms, including Rat-Flea Typhus, Rickettsia felis spotted fever, Urban Typhus of Malaya, cat flea rickettsiosis, fleaborne typhus, murine typhus, toulon typhus, and urban typhus. Additionally, it has a related synonym, Shop typhus.

Aneruptive fever is a type of spotted fever and has an exact synonym: Rickettsia helvetica spotted fever. It has a material basis in Rickettsia helvetica and is transmitted by ticks, specifically Ixodes, through tick-borne transmission. The symptoms of aneruptive fever include fever, headache, and myalgia. Essentially, it's a condition defined by its causal relationship with Rickettsia helvetica, its mode of transmission, and its clinical manifestations.

Sennetsu fever is a primary bacterial infectious disease that has a material basis in Neorickettsia sennetsu and is transmitted through vehicle-borne ingestion, specifically by the ingestion of raw or under-cooked gray mullet fish infected with trematodes. This disease is characterized by a variety of symptoms, including fever, malaise, anorexia, lymphadenopathy, hepatosplenomegaly, fatigue, chills, headache, backache, enlargement of lymph nodes, and myalgia. It is also known by its exact synonym, Sennetsu ehrlichiosis.

Exanthem is a type of skin disease and is characterized as something that at least has the symptom of some rash. It is defined as a skin disease that is characterized by a rash resulting from a variety of causes, including bacteria, viruses, toxins, drugs, and autoimmune disorders.

Bacterial exanthem is a type of exanthem, a bacterial infectious disease, and something that at least has a material basis in some bacteria.
