It is defined as an exanthem that is characterized by a diffuse, reddened, blanchable, finely papular, sandpaper-like rash due to infection by group A streptococcus and the production of an erythrogenic toxin.

Early congenital syphilis is a specific type of congenital syphilis that is transmitted through placental transmission. It is characterized by various symptoms including hepatosplenomegaly, hydrocephalus, skin lesions, seizures, failure to thrive, enlargement of lymph nodes, lymphadenopathy, and meningitis. Moreover, this condition is associated with abnormalities of prenatal development or birth and presents features such as intellectual disability and choroiditis. Early congenital syphilis is defined as a congenital syphilis that manifests during the first 3 months of life, with symptoms such as skin lesions, lymphadenopathy, hepatosplenomegaly, failure to thrive, blood-stained nasal discharge, perioral fissures, meningitis, choroiditis, hydrocephalus, seizures, intellectual disability, osteochondritis, and pseudoparalysis.
A multinodular goiter is a type of goiter characterized by a multinodular enlargement of the thyroid gland.

Parenchymatous neurosyphilis is a type of tertiary neurosyphilis characterized by various symptoms, including lethargy, headache, insomnia, irritability, fatigue, and difficulty concentrating. This condition is defined as a tertiary neurosyphilis that results when chronic meningoencephalitis leads to the destruction of cortical parenchyma. The infection manifests through symptoms such as irritability, difficulty concentrating, deterioration of memory, defective judgment, headaches, insomnia, fatigue, and lethargy.

Meningovascular neurosyphilis is a type of tertiary neurosyphilis characterized by a variety of symptoms, including paralysis, muscle weakness, stiff neck, urinary incontinence, headache, memory loss, insomnia, dizziness, and memory impairment. It is also associated with the disease feature of muscular atrophy. Specifically, meningovascular neurosyphilis results in inflammation located in the arteries of the brain or spinal cord. This condition manifests with symptoms such as headache, neck stiffness, dizziness, behavioral abnormalities, poor concentration, memory loss, lassitude, insomnia, blurred vision, weakness and wasting of shoulder-girdle and arm muscles, slowly progressive leg weakness with urinary or fecal incontinence or both, and paralysis of the legs due to thrombosis of spinal arteries.

Exanthema subitum, also known precisely as Roseola Infantum or Sixth Disease, is a type of viral infectious disease. This disease primarily affects infants and children, manifesting as an infection located in the skin. It has a material basis in either Human herpesvirus 6 or Human herpesvirus 7, which are part of the union of human betaherpesvirus 6 and human betaherpesvirus 7. The characteristic symptoms of exanthema subitum include a sudden high fever followed by a red rash that initially appears on the trunk before spreading to the legs and neck.

Variola major is a type of smallpox and is defined as a smallpox that results in a severe infection located in the skin and has a material basis in the Variola virus. The infection results in the formation of lesions.

Spinal polio is a type of paralytic poliomyelitis and is also categorized as a spinal cord disease. It is characterized by several symptoms, including hind limb paralysis and breathing problems. This condition specifically affects the spinal cord. It is defined as a paralytic poliomyelitis that results in the destruction located in the motor neurons of the spinal cord. The causative agents are Human poliovirus 1, Human poliovirus 2, or Human poliovirus 3. These viruses are typically transmitted either by ingestion of food or water contaminated with feces or by direct contact with oral secretions. Individuals infected with spinal polio may experience difficulty breathing and paralysis of the arms and legs.

Bulbospinal polio is a type of paralytic poliomyelitis that is characterized by several symptoms, including paralysis, dysphagia (difficulty swallowing), hind limb paralysis, and breathing problems. This condition specifically affects areas that are a combination of the spinal cord and the brainstem. It is defined as a paralytic poliomyelitis that leads to the destruction located in the motor neurons of the brainstem or the spinal cord. This condition can be caused by Human poliovirus 1, Human poliovirus 2, or Human poliovirus 3. These viruses are transmitted either by ingestion of food or water contaminated with feces or by direct contact with oral secretions. The infection manifests with symptoms such as difficulty breathing, difficulty swallowing, and paralysis of the arms and legs.

Paralytic poliomyelitis is a type of poliomyelitis and a central nervous system disease characterized by being a form of poliomyelitis that at least presents symptoms such as flaccid paralysis. Additionally, it is a type of condition where the disease is localized in the central nervous system. Paralytic poliomyelitis is defined as a poliomyelitis that leads to the destruction of motor neurons in the central nervous system. This condition is caused by Human poliovirus 1, Human poliovirus 2, or Human poliovirus 3. These viruses can be transmitted through the ingestion of food or water contaminated with feces or through direct contact with oral secretions. The infection manifests with symptoms including the loss of reflexes, muscle spasms, and acute flaccid paralysis.

O'nyong-nyong fever is a viral infectious disease characterized by symptoms such as joint pain, rash, fever, and lymphadenitis. It is caused by the Onyong-nyong virus, which is transmitted by Anopheles gambiae and Anopheles funestus mosquitoes. This disease specifically results in an infection located in the joints, highlighting its significant impact on those affected.

Barmah Forest virus disease is a type of viral infectious disease that has its material basis in the Barmah Forest virus. This disease is characterized by symptoms such as joint pain, rash, and fever. It is defined as a viral infectious disease that results in an infection located in the joint, transmitted by mosquito bites, and has symptoms including fever, arthralgia, and rash.

Ross River fever is a type of viral infectious disease and has an exact synonym, Ross River virus disease. It has a material basis in the Ross River virus and is transmitted by the Culex genus, as well as by Aedes mosquitoes. This disease results in an infection located in the joint and is characterized by symptoms such as joint pain, rash, and fever.

Oropouche fever is a viral infectious disease characterized by being caused by the Oropouche virus and transmitted by the Culicoides genus, specifically through the biting midge, Culicoides paraensis. It manifests with several symptoms including fever, chills, headache, anorexia, muscle pain, joint pain, and vomiting. This comprehensive definition encapsulates the disease's nature, its material basis, mode of transmission, and its symptomatic profile.

Balkan hemorrhagic fever, a specific type of Hantavirus hemorrhagic fever with renal syndrome, is characterized by its transmission and symptoms. It is transmitted by the yellow-necked field mouse, Apodemus flavicollis, and results from an infection located in the kidney caused by the Dobrava-Belgrade virus. The symptoms of Balkan hemorrhagic fever include headache, fever, muscle pains, facial flushing, petechiae, proteinuria, and renal failure.

Adult T cell leukemia lymphoma is a type of T cell acute lymphoblastic leukemia, which is also a viral infectious disease. It has a material basis in Human T cell leukemia virus type I and starts its existence during adult onset. The disease is transmitted by contact transmission, vehicle borne ingestion transmission, and vehicle borne medical transmission. It is defined as a T-cell acute leukemia that results in an abnormal increase of lymphocytes, derives from T-cells, and has a material basis in Human T-lymphotropic virus 1 (HTLV-1). This virus is transmitted by sexual contact, contaminated needles used by intravenous drug users, and breast feeding, which results in the formation of skin lesions. Moreover, Adult T cell leukemia lymphoma has the exact synonyms "Adult T-cell leukemia/lymphoma (HTLV-1 positive)" and "adult T-cell leukemia."

Maturity onset diabetes of the young (MODY) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a variety of diabetes mellitus that specifically has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by mutations in the MODY genes that affect beta-cell function, typically manifesting before 25 years of age and resulting from primary insulin secretion defects. This condition is also precisely known as MODY and Mason-type diabetes.

Gamstorp Wohlfart syndrome is a type of syndrome that exhibits symptoms including some progressive weakness. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by progressive weakness and atrophy of muscles in feet, legs, and hands. In some patients, the syndrome also leads to decreased sensitivity to touch, heat, or cold, particularly in the lower arms or legs. Furthermore, Gamstorp Wohlfart syndrome is exactly synonymous with autosomal recessive neuromyotonia and axonal neuropathy, as well as myokymia, myotonia, and muscle wasting.

Nonphotosensitive trichothiodystrophy 4 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which also falls under the category of nonphotosensitive trichothiodystrophy. This condition can be considered as something that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by brittle hair, short stature, decreased fertility, and cognitive impairment without photosensitivity, which has its material basis in mutations in the TTDN1 gene. Moreover, nonphotosensitive trichothiodystrophy 4 is exactly synonymous with several terms including AMISH BRITTLE HAIR BRAIN SYNDROME, BIDS syndrome, HAIR-BRAIN SYNDROME, and TTD4.

Adult spinal muscular atrophy is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of spinal muscular atrophy. It is characterized by having a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance and is known for symptoms such as muscle weakness and progressive weakness. This condition typically begins during adult onset. Adult spinal muscular atrophy is defined as a spinal muscular atrophy that is characterized by progressive muscular weakness and motor disability, which usually presents in the third decade of life. This condition is caused by mutations in the SMN1 or SMN2 genes, which are essential for the survival of motor neurons. It is also known by several exact synonyms including SMA4, SPINAL MUSCULAR ATROPHY, ADULT FORM, SPINAL MUSCULAR ATROPHY, TYPE IV, and spinal muscular atrophy 4.

Intermediate Spinal Muscular Atrophy (SMA) is an autosomal recessive disease, which falls under the category of childhood spinal muscular atrophy. This condition is characterized by having a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance and manifests symptoms such as muscle weakness and progressive weakness. The onset of Intermediate SMA typically begins during childhood. It is defined as a type of childhood spinal muscular atrophy marked by progressive muscular weakness and respiratory failure, developing in children between the ages of 6 and 12 months, significantly reducing life expectancy. This condition is caused by mutations in the SMN1 or SMN2 genes, which are essential for motor neuron survival.

Intermediate Spinal Muscular Atrophy is also known by several exact synonyms, including Muscular Atrophy, Spinal, Infantile Chronic Form; Muscular Atrophy, Spinal, Intermediate Type; SMA II; SMA2; Spinal Muscular Atrophy 2; and Spinal Muscular Atrophy Type II.

Congenital stationary night blindness is a physical disorder, which is also a type of hereditary night blindness and is categorized under diseases that have their basis in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a hereditary night blindness characterized by hemeralopia with a moderate loss of visual acuity, caused by defective photoreceptor-to-bipolar cell signaling, with common electroretinogram (ERG) findings of reduced or absent b-waves and generally normal a-waves. Additionally, congenital stationary night blindness has an exact synonym, which is congenital essential nyctalopia.

Exudative vitreoretinopathy is a type of retinal vascular disease and also a type of condition that at least has the symptom of some hemorrhage. It is defined as a retinal vascular disease characterized by the prevention of blood vessel formation at the edges of the retina and the hemorrhage of the blood vessels in the retina. Additionally, exudative vitreoretinopathy has the exact synonyms FEVR and familial exudative vitreoretinopathy.

Posterior polar cataract is a type of cataract characterized by a distinctive discoid lens opacity situated posteriorly and adjacent to the posterior capsule. It is also exactly synonymous with CATARACT, POSTERIOR POLAR.

Charcot Marie Tooth disease type 1 is a type of Charcot Marie Tooth disease that is characterized by the demyelination of the peripheral nerve axons. It is also known by the exact synonym, hereditary motor and sensory neuropathy type 1.

Charcot Marie Tooth disease type 2 is a specific type of Charcot Marie Tooth disease, characterized by abnormalities in the axon of the peripheral nerve cell. It is also known by exact synonyms including hereditary motor and sensory neuropathy Guadalajara neuronal type, hereditary motor and sensory neuropathy Okinawa type, and hereditary motor and sensory neuropathy type 2.

Charcot Marie Tooth Disease Type 3 is a type of Charcot Marie Tooth Disease and is characterized by motor and sensory peripheral neuropathies caused by demyelination. It is known by the exact synonyms Dejerine-Sottas Neuropathy and Dejerine-Sottas Syndrome. This disease is both a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of autosomal recessive disease, indicating that it has a material basis in some form of both autosomal dominant and autosomal recessive inheritance.

Charcot Marie Tooth disease type 4 is a type of Charcot Marie Tooth disease that is characterized by demyelinating or axonal abnormalities, which has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Additionally, it has an exact synonym: hereditary motor and sensory neuropathy.

Charcot Marie Tooth disease type X is a variant of Charcot Marie Tooth disease characterized by its definition: a Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease that results from an X-linked inheritance of a point mutation in the connexin-32 gene.

Charcot Marie Tooth disease intermediate type is a type of Charcot Marie Tooth disease and is characterized by a Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease where the motor conduction velocities fall above and below 38 m/s. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with both Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease dominant intermediate and Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease recessive intermediate.

Hypermethioninemia is a type of amino acid metabolic disorder defined by an excess of the amino acid methionine in the blood. This condition arises when methionine is not properly broken down in the body.

Visceral heterotaxy is a type of physical disorder, which is characterized by the abnormal distribution of the major visceral organs within the chest and abdomen. It is also known by its exact synonyms: heterotaxia and situs ambiguus.

Congenital adrenal insufficiency is classified as a type of autosomal dominant disease and also as a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is recognized as a physical disorder and an adrenal gland disease. This condition is characterized by being associated with material bases in both some autosomal dominant and autosomal recessive inheritances. Furthermore, it is linked to abnormalities in prenatal development or birth. The definition of congenital adrenal insufficiency highlights it as an adrenal gland disease characterized by cortisol deficiency, hypoaldosteronism, and the presence of either excessive or insufficient sex hormones. This condition is caused by mutations in the genes for 21-hydroxylase, 11beta-hydroxylase, 3beta-hydroxysteroid, 17alpha-hydroxylase, or 20,22-desmolase. Congenital adrenal insufficiency is also known by its exact synonyms: ADRENAL INSUFFICIENCY, CONGENITAL, WITH 46,XY SEX REVERSAL, PARTIAL OR COMPLETE; Adrenal insufficiency, congenital, with 46,XY sex reversal; and P450scc DEFICIENCY.

Familial medullary thyroid carcinoma is a type of thyroid gland medullary carcinoma and has an exact synonym, THYROID CARCINOMA, FAMILIAL MEDULLARY. It is defined as a thyroid gland medullary carcinoma that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance.

Hereditary sensory neuropathy is a type of neuropathy characterized by congenital insensitivity to pain, leading to ulceration of the fingers, tongue, lips, and other distal appendages. It is also known by its exact synonyms, familial dysautonomia, type II, and hereditary sensory and autonomic neuropathy.

Saldino Noonan Syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease that has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance, and it is characterized by congenital heart defects, failure to thrive, short stature, cognitive dysfunction, pectus excavatum, coagulation defects, and craniofacial defects. This syndrome is caused by a mutation in the Ras/mitogen-activated protein kinase. It also has at least one symptom: heart failure. Furthermore, Saldino Noonan Syndrome is exactly synonymous with type I short rib polydactyly syndrome.

Proteasome Associated Autoinflammatory Syndrome 1 (PRAAS1) is recognized as a type of autosomal recessive disease, proteasome-associated autoinflammatory syndrome, and digenic disease. It is defined by its genetic basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and digenic inheritance. Specifically, PRAAS1 is characterized by an early childhood onset of annular erythematous plaques on the face and extremities, leading to partial lipodystrophy and laboratory evidence of immune dysregulation. This syndrome is caused by a homozygous mutation in the PSMB8 gene on chromosome 6p21 or a heterozygous mutation in the PSMB8 gene along with a heterozygous mutation in either the PSMA3 gene on chromosome 14q23 or in the PSMB4 gene on chromosome 1q21. Furthermore, PRAAS1 is known by several exact synonyms including CANDLE, JMP syndrome, JOINT CONTRACTURES, MUSCULAR ATROPHY, MICROCYTIC ANEMIA, AND PANNICULITIS-INDUCED LIPODYSTROPHY, NKJO, Nakajo-Nishimura syndrome, and chronic atypical neutrophilic dermatosis with lipodystrophy and elevated temperature syndrome.

X-linked sideroblastic anemia with ataxia is a type of sideroblastic anemia and is also a type of X-linked recessive disease, which indicates that it at least has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. This specific condition is characterized by decreased production of hemoglobin and ataxia, with its material basis being a mutation in the ABCB7 gene. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including Anemia sideroblastic and spinocerebellar ataxia, Anemia, sideroblastic, spinocerebellar ataxia, X-linked sideroblastic anaemia and ataxia, X-linked sideroblastic anaemia with ataxia, and X-linked sideroblastic anemia and ataxia.

Congenital muscular dystrophy is a type of physical disorder and a form of muscular dystrophy. It is characterized by symptoms such as muscle weakness and progressive weakness. This condition has its basis in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. Specifically, congenital muscular dystrophy is defined as a muscular dystrophy characterized by diminished muscle tone (hypotonia), progressive muscle weakness and degeneration (atrophy), abnormally fixed joints, spinal rigidity, and delays in reaching motor milestones such as sitting or standing unassisted.

Ullrich congenital muscular dystrophy is a type of congenital muscular dystrophy and is also known as Ullrich disease or Ullrich scleroatonic muscular dystrophy. It is characterized by muscle weakness and respiratory depression, with its material basis being mutations in the COL6A1, COL6A2, and COL6A3 genes that produce components of type VI collagen. This condition is identified as both an autosomal dominant and an autosomal recessive disease, indicating that it can have a material basis in either autosomal dominant or autosomal recessive inheritance. Furthermore, Ullrich congenital muscular dystrophy is associated with symptoms such as muscle weakness and its disease basis involves abnormalities of prenatal development or birth.

Fukuyama congenital muscular dystrophy is a type of congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy type A, which has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is characterized by symptoms such as muscle weakness. This condition is also associated with abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. Furthermore, it is defined as a congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy type A characterized by muscle weakness, failure to thrive, severe intellectual and developmental disability, impaired vision, and cardiac abnormalities, which is caused by mutations in the FKTN gene, responsible for producing the fukutin protein.

Walker Warburg Syndrome is a type of congenital muscular dystrophy, autosomal recessive disease, and it is something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a congenital muscular dystrophy characterized by hypotonia, seizures, severe intellectual and developmental disability, eye abnormalities, and early death, with its material basis in mutations in multiple genes including POMT1, POMT2, ISPD, FKTN, FKRP, and LARGE1. Furthermore, Walker Warburg Syndrome has exact synonyms such as HARD syndrome and cerebroocular dysplasia-muscular dystrophy syndrome.

Lennox Gastaut Syndrome (LGS), also known as Lennox syndrome, is a childhood electroclinical syndrome defined by frequent seizures and intellectual disability that manifest in early childhood. This syndrome is characterized as a type that typically begins during childhood onset.

West syndrome is a type of infancy electroclinical syndrome, which is also known as Infantile spasms syndrome. It is defined as an infancy electroclinical syndrome characterized by infantile spasms, hypsarrhythmia on electroencephalogram, and intellectual disability. Furthermore, West syndrome is something that begins during infantile onset, indicating its existence starts in infancy.

Nonsyndromic deafness is a type of auditory system disease and is defined as an auditory system disease associated with permanent hearing loss caused by damage to structures in the inner ear and/or the middle ear, which is not associated with other signs and symptoms. It is also exactly synonymous with nonsyndromic hearing loss and nonsyndromic hereditary hearing loss.

Autosomal dominant nonsyndromic deafness is a type of nonsyndromic deafness, autosomal dominant disease, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a nonsyndromic deafness characterized by an autosomal dominant inheritance mode. Additionally, it has an exact synonym: autosomal dominant deafness.

Autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness is categorized as a type of nonsyndromic deafness and falls under the broader classification of autosomal recessive diseases. It is defined by a type of condition that inherently possesses a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is characterized by a nonsyndromic deafness that is distinguished by an autosomal recessive mode of inheritance.

X-linked nonsyndromic deafness is a type of nonsyndromic deafness, a type of X-linked monogenic disease, and a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some X-linked inheritance. It is defined as a nonsyndromic deafness characterized by an X-linked inheritance mode and has the exact synonym "X-linked deafness."

Orofacial cleft is identified as a type of physical disorder and syndrome. It falls under the category that intersects with conditions that are both a physical disorder and at least one disease rooted in some symptom. Additionally, it is part of a group that encompasses conditions with a location in the soft palate, lip, or hard palate. The definition of orofacial cleft is a physical disorder characterized by cleft lip and/or cleft palate, leading to feeding, speech, and hearing issues due to developmental failures.

Spondylocostal dysostosis is a type of spinal disease and falls under the category of dysostosis. It is identified as a condition that specifically affects the vertebral column, a key component of the skeletal system. This disease is defined as a dysostosis that leads to the abnormal development of the vertebrae or ribs, causing the bones of the spine to be misshapen and abnormally joined together. Moreover, spondylocostal dysostosis is known by several exact synonyms including Jarcho-Levin syndrome, costovertebral dysplasia, spondylothoracic dysostosis, and spondylothoracic dysplasia.

Seckel syndrome, also known as Harper's syndrome, Virchow-Seckel dwarfism, bird-headed dwarfism, and microcephalic primordial dwarfism, is a type of syndrome and autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. The definition of Seckel syndrome encompasses a syndrome marked by intrauterine growth retardation and postnatal dwarfism, along with microcephaly and intellectual disability.

Congenital disorder of glycosylation type I is a type of congenital disorder of glycosylation and also falls under the category of diseases that have their basis in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a congenital disorder of glycosylation characterized by under-glycosylated serum glycoproteins.

Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation Type II is a type of Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation, and it is also categorized under conditions that arise from abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a congenital disorder of glycosylation that involves malfunctioning trimming or processing of the protein-bound oligosaccharide chain.

Cone rod dystrophy is a type of monogenic disease, a type of retinal degeneration, and a type of condition that has its basis in genes. It is defined as a retinal degeneration characterized by the progressive deterioration of the cone and rod photoreceptor cells. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with cone-rod retinal dystrophy.

2-Hydroxyglutaric aciduria is a type of amino acid metabolic disorder, defined as an autosomal recessive neurometabolic disorder. It is characterized by a significant elevation of urinary levels of hydroxyglutaric acid, causing progressive brain damage.

L-2-hydroxyglutaric aciduria is a type of 2-hydroxyglutaric aciduria and also a type of cerebellar disease. It is characterized by being a condition where the disease affects the cerebellum, leading to issues with balance and muscle coordination (ataxia) due to damage to the cerebellum. It is specifically defined as an 2-hydroxyglutaric aciduria that involves damage to the cerebellum affecting movement coordination. Additionally, L-2-hydroxyglutaric aciduria has the exact synonym L-2-HYDROXYGLUTARIC ACIDEMIA.

D-2 hydroxyglutaric aciduria is a type of 2-hydroxyglutaric aciduria and is also a type of disease that has its location in the cerebrum. It is defined as an 2-hydroxyglutaric aciduria that involves developmental delay, seizures, weak muscle tone (hypotonia), and abnormalities in the cerebrum, which is responsible for controlling many important functions such as muscle movement, speech, vision, thinking, emotion, and memory.

Senior Loken syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by a syndrome that includes progressive wasting of the filtering unit of the kidney (nephronophthisis), with or without medullary cystic renal disease, and progressive eye disease. Senior Loken syndrome is also known by its exact synonyms: Loken Senior syndrome and renal-retinal syndrome.

Cranioectodermal dysplasia is a syndrome that also falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases and is a type of condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by sagittal craniosynostosis along with facial, ectodermal, and skeletal anomalies. Furthermore, cranioectodermal dysplasia is exactly synonymous with both Levin syndrome and Sensenbrenner syndrome.

Occult macular dystrophy is a type of macular degeneration, defined as a macular degeneration characterized by a central cone dysfunction leading to a loss of vision with a normal fundus and normal fluorescein angiography findings.

Glycogen Storage Disease XV (GSD XV) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of glycogen storage disease. It is characterized by muscle weakness and cardiac abnormalities, which are caused by mutations in the GYG1 gene that encodes glycogenin-1. This disease has several exact synonyms, including Glycogen Storage Disease 15, Glycogen Storage Disease Type XV, and Glycogen Storage Disease with Severe Cardiomyopathy due to Glycogenin Deficiency. The condition is also described as having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and presenting symptoms such as muscle weakness.
Hereditary lymphedema, a type of lymphedema, is commonly located in the legs and is caused by congenital abnormalities in the lymphatic system.

Brachydactyly is a type of dysostosis and has been characterized by short fingers and toes. It is recognized as a condition that at least manifests a phenotype of abnormal digit morphology. Additionally, brachydactyly is associated with diseases located at the intersection of the foot and finger. Furthermore, it has an exact match in the medical database MESH with the identifier D059327.

Gummatous syphilis is a type of tertiary syphilis that is defined by granulomatous lesions known as gummas. These lesions are characterized by a center of necrotic tissue with a rubbery texture. They can form in the liver, bones, and testes but may affect any organ.

Congenital generalized lipodystrophy is a type of disease that is autosomal recessive and can also be classified as a physical disorder as well as complete generalized lipodystrophy. This condition has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is rooted in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. It is defined by an extreme scarcity of subcutaneous fat, muscular hypertrophy, fatty liver, hypertriglyceridemia, and metabolic complications, including insulin resistance.
Trichotillomania is a type of impulse control disorder characterized by the uncontrollable plucking of one's hair.

Muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type b1 is a specific category within autosomal recessive diseases and muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type b. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and exhibits symptoms such as muscle weakness. This congenital muscular dystrophy is defined by muscle weakness, cognitive impairment, brain abnormalities, and is caused by a mutation in the POMT1 gene that encodes O-mannosyltransferase. It is precisely referred to as CMD due to dystroglycanopathy and Muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy congenital with impaired intellectual development B1.
Inflammatory bowel disease is a type of intestinal disease and is defined as an intestinal disease characterized by inflammation located in all parts of the digestive tract.

Severe congenital neutropenia is a type of physical disorder, neutropenia, and something that at least one disease has its basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a neutropenia characterized by a maturation arrest of granulopoiesis at the level of promyelocytes and early onset of severe bacterial infections.

Tooth agenesis is a type of tooth disease and also falls under the category of phenomena that invariably exhibit the phenotype of tooth agenesis. It is defined as a tooth disease characterized by the failure to develop one or more missing teeth. Moreover, tooth agenesis is precisely synonymous with familial tooth agenesis, hypodontia, oligodontia, and selective tooth agenesis.

Asphyxiating thoracic dystrophy is a type of bone development disease characterized by skeletal abnormalities that result in difficulty in breathing, caused by mutations leading to ciliopathy. It is also known by its exact synonyms: Jeune syndrome, short-rib thoracic dysplasia with or without polydactyly, and thoracic pelvic phalangeal dystrophy.

Primary congenital glaucoma is a type of glaucoma and a physical disorder, classified as a monogenic disease. It is characterized by a condition that arises from some abnormality in prenatal development or birth and has its basis in a gene mutation. Specifically, primary congenital glaucoma is defined as a glaucoma characterized by damage to the optic nerves, which reduces peripheral vision and leads to blindness. This condition has a material basis in a mutation in the MYOC gene and manifests before the age of 5 without other associated abnormalities.

Glycogen storage disease IX is a type of glycogen storage disease that is characterized by a deficiency of hepatic phosphorylase kinase activity. It also has the exact synonym "Glycogen storage disease 9."

Taeniasis is a type of parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease that has a material basis in either Taenia solium or Taenia saginata. This disease is transmitted through the ingestion of undercooked contaminated meat. It is also known by several related synonyms, including Beef tapeworm infection, Infection by Taeniarhynchus saginatus, and Taenia saginata infectious disease.

Intestinal schistosomiasis is a type of schistosomiasis, which also classifies as a type of intestinal disease. This condition is characterized by a phenotype that includes eosinophilia and presents with symptoms such as hepatosplenomegaly, hematochezia, abdominal pain, diarrhea, fever, cough, and rectorrhagia. Additionally, the disease primarily affects the intestine. Intestinal schistosomiasis is defined as a schistosomiasis that involves a parasitic infection of the intestine caused by Schistosoma mansoni, Schistosoma intercalatum, or Schistosomiasis japonicum, with symptoms comprising fever, cough, abdominal pain, diarrhea, hepatosplenomegaly, colonic polyposis with bloody diarrhea, and eosinophilia. Furthermore, intestinal schistosomiasis is also known by several exact synonyms, including Katayama fever, Schistosoma japonicum infection, Schistosoma mansoni infectious disease, and schistosomiasis japonica.

Extrapulmonary tuberculosis is a type of tuberculosis and a kind of disease that has a presence in the genitourinary system. It is defined as a tuberculosis that occurs at body sites other than the lung.

Abdominal tuberculosis is a type of extrapulmonary tuberculosis defined as an extrapulmonary tuberculosis that is located in the gastrointestinal tract, peritoneum, omentum, mesentery, liver, spleen, or pancreas.

ABCD syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease and syndrome that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by albinism, black lock, cell migration disorder of the neurocytes of the gut, and sensorineural deafness, and it has a material basis in a mutation in the endothelin B receptor gene (EDNRB). Additionally, ABCD syndrome has the exact synonyms ABCDS and albinism, black lock, cell migration disorder of the neurocytes of the gut, and deafness.

Adult syndrome is a type of syndrome that falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases and is characterized by a specific set of symptoms. These symptoms include light pigmentation with excessive freckling, sparse hair involving the scalp and axilla, lacrimal duct stenosis or atresia, onychodysplasia, hypodontia or early loss of permanent teeth, athelia or hypoplastic nipples, and breast hypoplasia, all of which have a material basis in a mutation in the TP63 gene. Additionally, adult syndrome is exactly synonymous with acro-dermato-ungual-lacrimal-tooth syndrome, indicating it is also identified by this name. This syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Triple A syndrome, also known precisely as AAAS, Achalasia-Addisonianism-Alacrimia syndrome, or Allgrove Syndrome, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and syndrome. It is characterized by a triad of achalasia, adrenal insufficiency, and alacrima. This syndrome has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is caused by mutations in the AAAS gene. These mutations lead to a defective ALADIN protein within the nuclear envelope, resulting in autonomic nervous system dysfunction.

Acheiropody is a type of autosomal recessive disease, osteochondrodysplasia, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an osteochondrodysplasia characterized by a lack of formation of the distal extremities, which has its material basis in a mutation in the LMBR1 gene. Acheiropody is also exactly synonymous with Acheiropodia and Horn-Kolb Syndrome.

Acrocapitofemoral dysplasia is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease and osteochondrodysplasia, which essentially means it is a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an osteochondrodysplasia characterized by skeletal dysplasia, bradydactyly, and a narrow thorax, with its material basis in mutations in the Indian hedgehog homolog gene.

Acrodermatitis enteropathica is a type of metal metabolism disorder and is also a condition that falls under the category of diseases with a basis in some structural variant. It is defined as a metal metabolism disorder characterized by dermatitis around bodily openings and the tips of fingers and toes, alopecia, and diarrhea. This condition has its material basis in a mutation in the SLC39A4 gene that encodes a zinc uptake protein, resulting in zinc deficiency.

Acrokeratosis verruciformis is a type of autosomal dominant disease and keratosis, which specifically has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a keratosis that arises from mutations in the ATP2A2 gene. Acrokeratosis verruciformis is also precisely known by its exact synonyms, Acrokeratosis verruciformis of Hopf and Hopf disease.

Askin's tumor is a type of Ewing sarcoma and is defined as an Ewing sarcoma that arises from the soft tissues of the chest wall, which tends to recur locally and not widely disseminated. It is also exactly synonymous with Askin tumor, Askin tumour, and Askin's tumour.

Oral cavity carcinoma in situ is equivalent to an intersection of in situ carcinoma and diseases that are located in the oral cavity. It is categorized as both a type of mouth disease and a type of in situ carcinoma. The definition of oral cavity carcinoma in situ is an in situ carcinoma of the oral cavity that is located in the epithelium, being the most common cause of leukoplakia and associated with the development of squamous cell carcinoma.

Pharynx carcinoma in situ is defined as an in situ carcinoma of the pharynx that is located in the epithelium and is associated with the development of squamous cell carcinoma. This condition is the same as the intersection of something that is an in situ carcinoma and something that is a disease with its location in the pharynx. Moreover, pharynx carcinoma in situ is a type of in situ carcinoma.

Gallbladder carcinoma in situ is defined as an in situ carcinoma located in the surface epithelium of the gallbladder that most commonly develops into adenocarcinoma. It is the same as something that is the intersection of something that is an in situ carcinoma and something that is at least a disease with a location in the gallbladder. Moreover, gallbladder carcinoma in situ is a type of gallbladder disease as well as a type of in situ carcinoma.

Bile duct carcinoma in situ is defined as an in situ carcinoma located in the surface epithelium of the bile duct, which most commonly develops into adenocarcinoma. This condition is the same as something that intersects with in situ carcinoma and a disease that has a location in the bile duct. Furthermore, bile duct carcinoma in situ is classified as a type of bile duct disease as well as a type of in situ carcinoma.

Bronchus carcinoma in situ is defined as an in situ carcinoma that is located in the bronchus and most commonly develops into adenocarcinoma. It is the same as the intersection of something that is an in situ carcinoma and something that has at least a disease located in either the bronchus or the bronchiole. Furthermore, bronchus carcinoma in situ is classified as a type of bronchial disease as well as a type of in situ carcinoma.

Respiratory system cancer is defined as an organ system cancer located in the respiratory system, characterized by uncontrolled cellular proliferation in the respiratory tract. It is identified as the same as something that intersects cancer and a disease with at least some location in the respiratory system. Furthermore, respiratory system cancer is recognized as a type of organ system cancer and a type of respiratory system disease.

Paranasal sinus cancer is equivalent to a condition that is both a cancer and a disease located in the paranasal sinuses. It is identified as a type of cancer affecting the respiratory system, as well as a type of paranasal sinus disease. Specifically, it is categorized as a disease situated in the paranasal sinuses. The definition of paranasal sinus cancer specifies it as a respiratory system cancer located in the paranasal sinuses. This cancer is known by several exact synonyms including Epidermoid carcinoma of the paranasal sinus, Mucoepidermoid carcinoma of the Accessory sinus, Adenoid cystic carcinoma of the Accessory sinus, Paranasal sinus adenocarcinoma, Paranasal sinus adenoid cystic carcinoma, Paranasal sinus mucoepidermoid carcinoma, and Paranasal sinus squamous cell carcinoma. Additionally, it has related synonyms such as adenoid cystic carcinoma of the paranasal sinus and squamous cell carcinoma of the paranasal sinus.

Infiltrating renal pelvis transitional cell carcinoma is a type of renal pelvis transitional cell carcinoma, defined as a renal pelvis transitional cell carcinoma located in the transitional epithelium of the renal pelvis.

A respiratory system benign neoplasm is the same as something that is both a benign neoplasm and a disease located in the respiratory system. It is a type of organ system benign neoplasm as well as a type of respiratory system disease. The definition of a respiratory system benign neoplasm is an organ system benign neoplasm that is located in the respiratory system, extending from the nasal sinuses to the diaphragm.

Reproductive organ benign neoplasm is defined as an organ system benign neoplasm that is located in reproductive system organs. It is equivalent to something that is both a benign neoplasm and a disease located in the reproductive system. Furthermore, reproductive organ benign neoplasm is classified as a type of organ system benign neoplasm and also as a type of reproductive system disease.

A bladder benign neoplasm is the same as something that is an intersection of a benign neoplasm and something that is at least a disease located in the urinary bladder. It is a type of bladder disease as well as a type of urinary system benign neoplasm. Furthermore, a bladder benign neoplasm is defined as a urinary system benign neoplasm located in the bladder, including papillomas, leiomyomas, fibromas, hemangiomas, neurofibromas, and lipomas.

A gastrointestinal system benign neoplasm is equivalent to an intersection of a benign neoplasm and a disease that is located in the digestive system. It is a subtype of both organ system benign neoplasm and gastrointestinal system disease. Furthermore, a gastrointestinal system benign neoplasm is defined as an organ system benign neoplasm that is located in the organs of the gastrointestinal tract.

A biliary tract benign neoplasm, which is also precisely termed as an extrahepatic bile duct neoplasm, neoplasm of extrahepatic bile ducts, or tumor of the extrahepatic bile duct, is characterized as a type of hepatobiliary benign neoplasm and is a kind of biliary tract disease. It is defined as a hepatobiliary benign neoplasm located in the biliary tract and is the same as something that is the intersection of a benign neoplasm and something that at least has the location of some biliary tree disease.

A gastrointestinal neuroendocrine tumor is a type of gastrointestinal system cancer defined as a gastrointestinal system cancer that has its material basis in neuroendocrine cells. It is exactly synonymous with gastrointestinal neuroendocrine tumour, malignant gastrointestinal neuroendocrine tumor, and malignant gastrointestinal neuroendocrine tumour.

Advanced sleep phase syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and sleep disorder that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a sleep disorder involving an altered circadian rhythm, which results in falling asleep in the early evening and awakening very early in the morning. Additionally, advanced sleep phase syndrome is exactly synonymous with familial advanced sleep-phase syndrome.

Aicardi-Goutieres Syndrome (AGS) is a type of syndrome, which is a specific kind of autosomal genetic disease. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal inheritance. The definition of Aicardi-Goutieres Syndrome is a genetically heterogeneous encephalopathy, marked in its most severe form by cerebral atrophy, leukodystrophy, intracranial calcifications, chronic cerebrospinal fluid lymphocytosis, increased CSF alpha-interferon, and negative serologic investigations for common prenatal infections. AGS is also exactly synonymous with Cree encephalitis.

Aland Island eye disease is a type of X-linked recessive disease and an eye disease that fundamentally has a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance. The disease is defined as an eye condition characterized by fundus hypopigmentation, decreased visual acuity, nystagmus, astigmatism, myopia, defective darkness adaptation, and is caused by a mutation in the CACNA1F gene. Furthermore, Aland Island eye disease is also known by its exact synonyms, FORSIUS-ERIKSSON TYPE OCULAR ALBINISM and Forsius-Eriksson syndrome.

Allan Herndon Dudley Syndrome (AHDS), also known as Allan-Herndon Syndrome, is a type of X-linked recessive disease and syndrome. It is characterized by a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance. The definition of Allan Herndon Dudley Syndrome encompasses a syndrome that arises from a mutation in the gene encoding the monocarboxylate transporter-8. This mutation alters the structure and function of the SLC16A2 protein, rendering it incapable of transporting the thyroid triiodothyronine (T3) hormone into the nerve cells of the developing brain. As a result, it affects normal brain development, leading to intellectual disability and problems with movement.

Oculocutaneous albinism is a type of syndrome characterized by abnormal pigmentation of the skin, hair, and eyes. It is a type of autosomal recessive disease and has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance.

Ocular albinism 1 is a type of eye disease and has an exact synonym, Albinism ocular 1, as well as ocular albinism. It is defined as an eye disease that is characterized by reduced pigmentation of the iris, which results in the impairment of visual acuity without significantly affecting the color of skin or hair. This condition has its material basis in a mutation in the GPR143 gene that encodes segments of the melanosomes that store melanin.

Alopecia universalis is a type of alopecia and an autosomal recessive disease, which is characterized by the complete loss of hair on the scalp and body. This condition is also known as Alopecia Universalis Congenita. Moreover, it is described as something that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance.

Alternating hemiplegia of childhood (AHC) is a type of hemiplegia that begins in childhood and is characterized by recurrent episodes of temporary weakness or complete paralysis on one or both sides of the body. It is also known by its exact synonym, AHC.

Familial visceral amyloidosis is a type of autosomal dominant disease, an inherited metabolic disorder, and a form of amyloidosis that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an amyloidosis characterized by the abnormal deposition of amyloid proteins located in the visceral organs, primarily affecting the kidneys. Additionally, familial visceral amyloidosis is exactly synonymous with AMYLOIDOSIS, FAMILIAL RENAL, German type amyloidosis, OSTERTAG TYPE AMYLOIDOSIS, and systemic nonneuropathic amyloidosis.

Finnish type amyloidosis, also precisely known as AGel amyloidosis, AMYLOIDOSIS, MERETOJA TYPE, Lattice corneal dystrophy type II, and gelsolin amyloidosis, is a type of primary cutaneous amyloidosis, autosomal dominant disease, and eye disease. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and exhibits symptoms such as facial paralysis. The disease commonly affects the zone of skin, eyes, and nerves, featuring conditions like cutis laxa and lattice corneal dystrophy. Specifically, Finnish type amyloidosis is defined by the abnormal deposits of amyloid protein primarily impacting the eyes, nerves, and skin, which results from mutations in the gelsolin gene (GSN). This condition is associated with symptoms like corneal lattice dystrophy, bilateral facial paralysis, and cutis laxa.

Transthyretin amyloidosis is a type of autosomal dominant disease, heart disease, inherited metabolic disorder, and amyloidosis. It is characterized by a loss of sensation in the extremities, cardiomyopathy, nephropathy, vitreous opacities, and central nervous system amyloidosis, which results from abnormal deposits of amyloid protein in the body's organs and tissues. The condition is due to autosomal dominant inheritance of mutations in the TTR gene. Furthermore, transthyretin amyloidosis is known to at least have a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and its disease can have locations in the heart and nerves.

Additionally, transthyretin amyloidosis is also referred to by several exact synonyms including ATTR amyloidosis, ATTRm amyloidosis, Amyloidosis, hereditary, transthyretin-related, Corino de Andrade's disease, Familial transthyretin amyloidosis, TTR amyloidosis, familial amyloid polyneuropathy, paramyloidosis, and transthyretin-related hereditary amyloidosis.

Primary cutaneous amyloidosis, which is synonymous with PCA and familial primary localized cutaneous amyloidosis, is defined as an amyloidosis characterized by pruritus, skin scratching, and by deposits of amyloid in the dermis. It is a specific type of amyloidosis that intersects with diseases located in the skin zone. This condition is a type of skin disease, an inherited metabolic disorder, and also falls under diseases that have a basis in some structural variant.

Anauxetic dysplasia 1 is a specific type of anauxetic dysplasia and is categorized as an autosomal recessive disease. It is defined by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, anauxetic dysplasia 1 arises due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the RMRP gene located on chromosome 9p13. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with spondylometaepiphyseal dysplasia, Menger type.

Rh deficiency syndrome is a type of hemolytic anemia characterized by the deficiency of Rh antigens. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the RHAG gene located on chromosome 6p12.
Hypochromic microcytic anemia is a type of microcytic anemia characterized by paler than normal blood cells.

Arterial calcification of infancy is a type of artery disease that begins during infantile onset and affects the arteries. It is defined as a vascular disease characterized by generalized calcification of the arterial internal elastic lamina, leading to the rupture of the lamina and occlusive changes in the tunica intima with stenosis and decreased elasticity of the vessel wall. It is also known by its exact synonyms: generalized arterial calcification of infancy, idiopathic infantile arterial calcification, and infantile arteriosclerosis.

Arterial tortuosity syndrome is a type of connective tissue disease, which is defined as a connective tissue disorder characterized by the elongation and generalized tortuosity of the major arteries, including the aorta.

Distal arthrogryposis is a type of muscle tissue disease characterized by congenital joint contractures of the hand and feet. It is also known by its exact synonym, Arthrogryposis Multiplex Congenita.

Arts syndrome is a type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, characterized by profound congenital sensorineural hearing impairment, early-onset hypotonia, delayed motor development, mild to moderate intellectual disability, ataxia, and an increased risk of infection. The disease has its material basis in mutations of the PRPS1 gene. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including ARTS, Lethal ataxia with deafness and optic atrophy, MRXS18, MRXSARTS, fatal X-linked ataxia with deafness and loss of vision, syndromic X-linked mental retardation 18, and syndromic X-linked mental retardation Arts type.

Atelosteogenesis is a type of spinal disease and a type of osteochondrodysplasia, which is a condition that affects the vertebral column. It is defined as an osteochondrodysplasia characterized by specific patterns of aplasia/hypoplasia of humeri, femora, and the spine in newborns.

Atransferrinemia is a type of disease that falls under several categories: it is an autosomal recessive disease, a metal metabolism disorder, and it is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, Atransferrinemia is defined as a metal metabolism disorder characterized by transferrin deficiency, microcytic anemia, and iron loading. This condition is caused by autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the structural gene for transferrin (TF) located on chromosome 3q22. Additionally, Atransferrinemia is also known by the exact synonym familial hypotransferrinemia.

Familial atrial fibrillation is a type of atrial fibrillation and is also a type of condition that has at least some symptoms of atrial fibrillation. It is defined as an atrial fibrillation that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance of the familial atrial fibrillation (ATFB) genes. Additionally, familial atrial fibrillation has the exact synonym ATFB.

Atrioventricular septal defect is a type of heart septal defect that is the same as something that intersects heart disease and a disease located in the atrioventricular septum. It is defined as a congenital heart septal defect characterized by an abnormal or inadequate fusion of the superior and inferior endocardial cushions with the mid portion of the atrial septum and the muscular portion of the ventricular septum, thus allowing extra blood to circulate the lungs. This condition has exact synonyms, including AVCD (Atrioventricular Canal Defect), AVSD, ECD (Endocardial Cushion Defect), and is also referred to as an endocardial cushion defect.
Baller Gerold syndrome is a type of synostosis, which is defined as a synostosis characterized by coronal craniosynostosis, short stature, and aplasia or hypoplasia of the radial bone.

Bamforth-Lazarus syndrome is a type of hypothyroidism that is characterized by thyroid dysgenesis, cleft palate, spiky hair, and bifid epiglottis. It has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the FKHL15 gene on chromosome 9q22. This condition also has an exact synonym: Hypothyroidism, Athyroidal, with Spiky Hair and Cleft Palate.

Pseudo torch syndrome 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, syndrome, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by congenital microcephaly, intracranial calcifications, severe developmental delay, simplified gyration, and polymicrogyria that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the OCLN gene on chromosome 5q13.2. Pseudo torch syndrome 1 is also known by several exact synonyms including BLC-PMG, BLCPMG, Baraitser-Brett-Piesowicz syndrome, Baraitser-Reardon syndrome, PTORCH1, band-like calcification with simplified gyration and polymicrogyria, bilateral band-like calcification with polymicrogyria, and microcephaly-intracranial calcification-intellectual disability syndrome.

Bannayan Riley Ruvalcaba syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and Cowden syndrome, which essentially means it stems from a category that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. This syndrome is characterized by macrocephaly, multiple noncancerous tumors and hamartomas, and dark freckles on the penis. The condition is caused by a heterozygous germline mutation in the PTEN gene on chromosome 10q23. Additionally, Bannayan Riley Ruvalcaba syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms, including Bannayan-Zonana syndrome, Cowden syndrome 1, Riley-Smith syndrome, and Ruvalcaba-Myhre-Smith syndrome.

Bart Pumphrey syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a syndrome that has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by leukonychia, wart-like skin growths, palmoplantar keratoderma, and hearing loss, which is due to a heterozygous mutation in the GJB2 gene on chromosome 13q12. Additionally, Bart Pumphrey syndrome has an exact synonym: Knuckle Pads, Leukonychia, and Sensorineural Deafness.

Biotin responsive basal ganglia disease falls under the category of basal ganglia disease. It is characterized by a range of symptoms including ataxia, confusion, seizures, and dysphagia. Additionally, this condition features dystonia as a notable aspect. Biotin responsive basal ganglia disease is specifically defined as a basal ganglia disease marked by recurrent subacute encephalopathy, exhibiting symptoms such as confusion, seizures, ataxia, dystonia, supranuclear facial palsy, external ophthalmoplegia, and dysphagia.

Beare Stevenson Cutis Gyrata Syndrome is a type of syndrome that falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases. It specifically arises from a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This syndrome is defined by its distinct features, including cutis gyrata, acanthosis nigricans, and craniosynostosis. These characteristics are due to a heterozygous mutation in the FGFR2 gene located on chromosome 10q26.

Vitelliform macular dystrophy is a type of macular degeneration defined by the disruption of cells in a small area near the center of the retina, the macula, which may cause progressive vision loss. It has exact synonyms including Best disease, Best macular dystrophy, and juvenile-onset vitelliform macular dystrophy.

Bestrophinopathy is a type of macular degeneration characterized by central vision loss, an absent electrooculogram light rise, and a reduced electroretinogram. It has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the BEST1 gene on chromosome 11q12. Furthermore, bestrophinopathy is exactly synonymous with autosomal recessive bestrophinopathy.

Bethlem myopathy is a type of congenital muscular dystrophy and has another name, benign congenital muscular dystrophy. It is defined as a congenital muscular dystrophy characterized by myopathy and joint contractures that progresses slowly. The condition is caused by an autosomal dominant inheritance of a heterozygous mutation in the COL6A1 gene, the COL6A2 gene, or the COL6A3 gene.

Bietti crystalline corneoretinal dystrophy, also known exactly as Bietti's crystalline dystrophy, is a type of retinal degeneration. It is defined as a retinal degeneration that is characterized by the presence of crystals in the cornea, shiny deposits on the retina, and progressive atrophy of the retina, choriocapillaris, and choroid. This condition has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CYP4V2 gene located on chromosome 4q35.

Fetal alcohol syndrome is a type of fetal alcohol spectrum disorder characterized by severe mental and physical defects that can develop in a child when the mother drinks alcohol during pregnancy. This condition is a result of alcohol serving as a disease driver and is defined by features including craniofacial dysmorphology (microcephaly, smooth philtrum, thin upper lip, small eye openings), pre- and postnatal growth deficiency, and central nervous system dysfunction. It falls under the category of conditions that have neurodevelopmental abnormalities as a phenotype and start during pediatric onset.

Partial fetal alcohol syndrome is a type of fetal alcohol spectrum disorder characterized by most, but not all, of the growth deficiency and/or craniofacial features of fetal alcohol syndrome, including central nervous system dysfunction due to prenatal alcohol exposure. This disorder emerges during pediatric onset and is driven by alcohol consumption. Additionally, it encompasses some neurodevelopmental abnormalities as part of its phenotype.

Alcohol-Related Neurodevelopmental Disorder (ARND), also known exactly as static encephalopathy, is a type of Fetal Alcohol Spectrum Disorder. It is defined as a disorder resulting from prenatal alcohol exposure, which leads to central nervous system dysfunction alongside behavioral and/or cognitive deficits. ARND falls under the category of conditions that inherently have some neurodevelopmental abnormality and typically begin during pediatric onset.

Alcohol-related birth defects (ARBD) are a type of fetal alcohol spectrum disorder that is characterized by damage to organs, bones, or muscles resulting from prenatal alcohol exposure. This condition begins during pediatric onset and is driven by alcohol as a disease factor. ARBD is also known by its exact synonym, ARBD.

Spastic cerebral palsy is a type of cerebral palsy defined by being caused by damage in the outer layer of the brain, the cerebral cortex. This results in increased tone, or tension, in a muscle, causing abnormal movements.

Ataxic cerebral palsy is a type of cerebral palsy and also falls under the category of conditions that typically exhibit hypotonia as part of their phenotype. It is defined as a cerebral palsy caused by damage to the cerebellum, impacting muscle coordination, especially in the limbs. This condition can lead to hypotonia, tremors, and challenges with visual and/or auditory processing. Ataxic cerebral palsy is exactly synonymous with hypotonic cerebral palsy.
Female breast cancer is a type of breast cancer with a definition as a breast cancer that develops from breast tissue in females.

Dyskinetic cerebral palsy, also precisely known as Athetoid Dyskinetic Cerebral Palsy, is a specific type of cerebral palsy characterized by a unique condition where individuals struggle to maintain an upright, steady position for activities such as sitting or walking, often displaying involuntary movements. This condition is caused by damage to the extrapyramidal motor system and/or pyramidal tract and to the basal ganglia, leading to mixed muscle tone, including both hypertonia and hypotonia. Moreover, dyskinetic cerebral palsy is categorized under conditions that exhibit some form of hypotonia as a phenotype.

Mixed cerebral palsy is a type of cerebral palsy characterized by a condition that arises due to injury to both the pyramidal and extra pyramidal areas of the brain. This results in both the tight muscle tone and involuntary movements, leading to difficulties with speaking and swallowing for the individual.

Congenital bile acid synthesis defect is a type of physical disorder that also falls under the category of steroid inherited metabolic disorders. It is recognized as a condition that originates from some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. This disorder is specifically defined as a steroid inherited metabolic disorder characterized by abnormal conversion of cholesterol into bile acids, predominantly occurring in the liver. It is exactly synonymous with 3-beta-hydroxy-delta-5-C27-steroid oxidoreductase deficiency, CBA, and cholestasis with delta(4)-3-oxosteroid-5-beta-reductase deficiency.

Birk Barel syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and syndrome that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by intellectual disability, hypotonia, hyperactivity, and facies, with its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the KCNK9 gene on chromosome 8q24. Moreover, it has the exact synonym Birk-Barel mental retardation dysmorphism syndrome.

Birt Hogg Dube syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease that is also a skin disease. It is a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. The syndrome is defined as a skin disease characterized by hair follicle hamartomas, kidney tumors, and spontaneous pneumothorax, which has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding folliculin (FLCN) on chromosome 17p11.

Bjornstad syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease, which specifically has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by early onset of hearing loss and hair loss due to pili torti, caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the BCS1L gene on chromosome 2q35. Moreover, Bjornstad syndrome is exactly synonymous with BJS, PTD, and deafness-pili torti-hypogonadism syndrome.

Blau syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a syndrome that has material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by familial granulomatous arthritis, uveitis, and skin granulomas, with this condition having a material basis in heterozygous mutations in the NOD2 gene. Moreover, Blau syndrome has exact synonyms including ARTHROCUTANEOUVEAL GRANULOMATOSIS, BLAUS, and Jabs syndrome.

Blue cone monochromacy is a type of X-linked recessive disease and a form of achromatopsia, which is characterized by severely impaired color discrimination, low visual acuity, nystagmus, and photophobia. This is due to the absence of functional long wavelength-sensitive and medium wavelength-sensitive cones in the retina. It occurs due to some material basis in recessive X-linked inheritance.

Boomerang dysplasia is a type of osteochondrodysplasia characterized by severe dwarfism, dislocated joints, club feet, distinctive facies, and dysplastic tubular bones with boomerang-like bowing. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the FLNB gene on chromosome 3p14.

Borjeson Forssman Lehmann syndrome is a type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, also known as a type of X-linked recessive disease, and is characterized by intellectual disability, truncal obesity, seizures, hypogonadism, developmental delay, distinctive facial features, tapered fingers, and short toes. It has a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance of mutations in the PHF6 gene. This syndrome is synonymously known as BFLS, BORJ, Borjeson syndrome, MRXSBFL, intellectual deficiency-epilepsy-endocrine disorders syndrome, mental retardation, epilepsy, and endocrine disorder, as well as syndromic X-linked mental retardation Borjeson-Forssman-Lehmann type.

Athabaskan brainstem dysgenesis syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of brain disease, specifically something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a brain disease characterized by brainstem dysgenesis, which has its material basis in homozygous mutations in the HOXA1 gene. Additionally, Athabaskan brainstem dysgenesis syndrome has an exact synonym: Navajo Brainstem Syndrome.

Bothnia retinal dystrophy is a type of fundus dystrophy characterized by early onset of night blindness and decreased visual acuity that progresses to blindness in early adulthood. This condition has its material basis in a mutation in the RLBP1 gene. Additionally, Bothnia retinal dystrophy is also known exactly as Vasterbotten dystrophy.

Bowen Conradi syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease and syndrome, which also falls under the category of disorders with a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by growth delays, failure to thrive, and malformations of the head and face, leading to infantile death, and has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the EMG1 gene on chromosome 12p13. Additionally, Bowen Conradi syndrome is exactly synonymous with BWCNS, Bowen Hutterite syndrome, and Bowen-Conradi Hutterite syndrome.

Small cell carcinoma is a type of carcinoma defined as an undifferentiated neoplasm composed of primitive-appearing cells. It has exact synonyms, including Small cell carcinoma - intermediate cell, Small cell carcinoma, intermediate cell, and intermediate cell small cell carcinoma.
Organ system cancer is a type of cancer that is classified based on the organ it starts in.

Cell type cancer is the same as something that intersects with something that is cancer and something that at least derives from some cell. Additionally, cell type cancer is classified as a type of cancer. It is defined as a cancer that is classified by the type of cell from which it is derived.

Anal canal cancer is the same as something that is both a cancer and a disease located in the anal canal. Additionally, anal canal cancer is a type of large intestine cancer with a definition as a large intestine cancer located in the terminal part of the large intestine.

Brachydactyly syndactyly syndrome is a type of syndrome that falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases, specifically being a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by brachydactyly and syndactyly, having its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the HOXD13 gene on chromosome 2q31.

Brachyolmia is a type of osteochondrodysplasia and it is characterized by generalized platyspondyly without significant long bone abnormalities and short stature. Additionally, brachyolmia has an exact synonym, brachyrachia.

Branchiooculofacial syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease, which at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by low birth weight and growth retardation, bilateral branchial clefts.

Brody myopathy is the same as something that intersects with a disease and something wherein at least one disease has a location in some skeletal muscle tissue. It is a type of atrophic muscular disease. Furthermore, Brody myopathy is defined as a neuromuscular disease characterized by difficulty relaxing muscles and muscle stiffness following exercise or other strenuous activity, and it is located in skeletal muscles.

Brooke Spiegler Syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant and skin disease, which is characterized by the development of several types of tumors from the skin due to a heterozygous mutation in the CYLD gene on chromosome 16q12. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including BRSS, BSS, CYLD cutaneous syndrome, SBS, and Spiegler-Brooke Syndrome.

Brown Vialetto Van Laere syndrome is a type of syndrome characterized by sensorineural hearing loss and a variety of cranial nerve palsies, usually involving the motor components of the seventh and ninth to twelfth cranial nerves. It has an exact match with the MESH code C537111.

Malignant pleural solitary fibrous tumor is a type of pleural cancer. It is defined as a pleural cancer that is located in mesenchymal cells in the areolar tissue subjacent to the mesothelial-lined pleura.

Fetal alcohol spectrum disorder is characterized as a specific developmental and physical disorder. It includes physical, behavioral, and learning birth defects resulting from maternal ingestion of alcohol during pregnancy. This condition falls under the category of specific developmental disorders and is driven at least in part by alcohol.
Chorioamnionitis is a type of placenta disease characterized by an inflammation of the fetal membranes (amnion and chorion) due to a bacterial infection.
Funisitis is a type of connective tissue disease, defined as an inflammation of the connective tissue of the umbilical cord.

Dent disease is a type of X-linked recessive disease, renal tubular transport disease, and is characterized by something that at least has a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance. It is defined as a renal tubular transport disease that is characterized by tubular proteinuria, hypercalciuria, calcium nephrolithiasis, nephrocalcinosis, and chronic kidney failure, with its material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance of mutations in the CLCN5 gene or OCRL1 gene. Moreover, Dent disease has exact synonyms: Dent disease 1, Dent disease 2, and Dent's disease.

Cardiomyopathy is a type of heart disease and is defined as a heart disease and a myopathy characterized by the deterioration of the heart muscle's function. It is also exactly synonymous with Cardiomyopathies.

Electroclinical syndrome is a type of epilepsy and has a definition as an epilepsy syndrome that is a group of clinical entities showing a cluster of electro-clinical characteristics. These are classified according to age at onset, cognitive and developmental antecedents and consequences, motor and sensory examinations, EEG features, provoking or triggering factors, and patterns of seizure occurrence with respect to sleep. Additionally, electroclinical syndrome has an exact synonym: electro-clinical syndrome.

Neonatal period electroclinical syndrome is a type of electroclinical syndrome that is defined as an electroclinical syndrome with onset in the neonatal period, specifically less than 44 weeks of gestational age.

Infancy electroclinical syndrome is a type of electroclinical syndrome and also falls under the category of conditions that begin during the infantile onset, specifically starting at an existence point between birth and one year of age. It is defined as an electroclinical syndrome with onset in infancy.

Childhood electroclinical syndrome is a type of absence epilepsy and a condition that initially manifests during childhood onset. It is defined as an electroclinical syndrome that begins in childhood between the ages of one and 12 years.

Adolescence adult electroclinical syndrome is a type of absence epilepsy and also a type of condition that begins during the period that encompasses both adult onset and young adult onset. It is defined as an electroclinical syndrome with onset in adolescence and adulthood.
Variable age at onset electroclinical syndrome is a type of electroclinical syndrome characterized by the development of seizures later in life, with a variable age of onset and duration.

Early onset absence epilepsy is a type of childhood electroclinical syndrome that begins during childhood. It is characterized as a childhood electroclinical syndrome marked by the occurrence of typical absence seizures, which start between the ages of four and ten years.

Early infantile epileptic encephalopathy is a type of neonatal period electroclinical syndrome that is characterized by tonic spasms and partial seizures. It also has the exact synonym "Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy with Burst-Suppression."

3-Methylcrotonyl-CoA carboxylase deficiency, also known as 3-Methylcrotonylglycinuria, 3MCC deficiency, and BMCC deficiency, is an autosomal recessive disease that intersects with amino acid metabolic disorders and diseases located in muscle tissue. It is specifically characterized by inadequate levels of the enzyme 3-methylcrotonyl-CoA carboxylase, which is essential for breaking down proteins containing the amino acid leucine. This condition is a type of muscular disease and amino acid metabolic disorder with a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Individuals with this condition may exhibit hypotonia (weak muscle tone) and skeletal muscle atrophy, alongside symptoms such as lethargy, poor feeding, diarrhea, and vomiting.

Aceruloplasminemia is a type of disease that falls under several categories: it is an autosomal recessive disease, an iron metabolism disease, and an inherited metabolic disorder. It is also defined as a condition that has at least a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Aceruloplasminemia is characterized by a mutation in the ceruloplasmin gene, leading to an iron metabolism disease. This mutation results in progressive neurodegeneration of the retina and basal ganglia, as well as diabetes mellitus.

AGAT deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease, cerebral creatine deficiency syndrome, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an amino acid metabolic disorder that has a material basis in a mutation in the GATM gene, resulting in a deficiency of arginine:glycine amidinotransferase, which then limits creatine synthesis. Additionally, AGAT deficiency has exact synonyms: Cerebral creatine deficiency syndrome 3 and arginine glycine amidinotransferase deficiency.

COX deficiency infantile mitochondrial myopathy is a type of cytochrome c oxidase deficiency disease characterized by myotonia, abnormalities of the heart and kidneys, and lactic acidosis. It is also known by exact synonyms including cardioencephalomyopathy, fatal infantile, due to cytochrome c oxidase deficiency; fatal infantile COX deficiency; fatal infantile cardioencephalomyopathy due to cytochrome c oxidase deficiency; fatal infantile cytochrome C oxidase deficiency; and fatal infantile encephalocardiomyopathy. Furthermore, COX deficiency infantile mitochondrial myopathy is precisely matched with ORDO:1561 and UMLS_CUI:C4273730.

Methylmalonic aciduria and homocystinuria type cblC is a type of digenic disease, which is also categorized under methylmalonic acidemia. This specific condition is an example of a disorder that arises from digenic inheritance, where the disease has a material basis. It is defined as a form of methylmalonic acidemia characterized by a deficiency in the synthesis of both AdoCbl and MeCbl (cblC), leading to decreased levels of the coenzymes adenosylcobalamin (AdoCbl) and methylcobalamin (MeCbl). This deficiency results in decreased activity of the enzyme methylmalonyl-CoA mutase. Additionally, methylmalonic aciduria and homocystinuria type cblC is exactly synonymous with Cobalamin C deficiency and MAHCC.
