Methylmalonic aciduria and homocystinuria type CBLD is a type of methylmalonic acidemia characterized by a combination of homocystinuria and methylmalonic aciduria, along with a deficiency of MCM and MS activities. It is also precisely known as Cobalamin D deficiency and MAHCD.

Methylmalonic aciduria and homocystinuria type cblF is a type of methylmalonic acidemia, characterized by the accumulation of cobalamin in lysosomes, which then prevents the synthesis of the cofactors adenosylcobalamin (AdoCbl) and methylcobalamin (MeCbl). This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the LMBRD1 gene on chromosome 6q13. It is also known exactly as Cobalamin F deficiency and MAHCF.
Vitamin metabolic disorder is a type of inherited metabolic disorder defined as an inherited metabolic disorder resulting from a deficiency in vitamin or vitamin cofactor transport or metabolism.

Cerebral folate receptor alpha deficiency is a type of vitamin metabolic disorder and an autosomal recessive disease, which at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is located in the cerebrum. It is defined as a vitamin metabolic disorder that has a material basis in mutations in the folate receptor 1 (FOLR1) gene coding for folate receptor alpha (FRalpha), is located in the brain, and is characterized by progressive movement disturbance, psychomotor decline, and epilepsy. Furthermore, it has an exact synonym: Neurodegeneration due to cerebral folate transport deficiency.

Ornithine translocase deficiency is a type of amino acid metabolic disorder, which is also a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some ammonia. This disorder is defined as an amino acid metabolic disorder that has its material basis in deficiency of ornithine translocase, resulting in the accumulation of ammonia in the blood. Additionally, ornithine translocase deficiency has exact synonyms, including HHH syndrome and Hyperornithinemia-Hyperammonemia-Homocitrullinuria (HHH) syndrome.
Serine deficiency is a type of amino acid metabolic disorder characterized by defects in the biosynthesis of the amino acid L-serine, which serves as its material basis.

PHGDH deficiency is a type of serine deficiency and has a definition as a serine deficiency that has its material basis in the deficiency of phosphoglycerate dehydrogenase, resulting in a disruption of L-serine biosynthesis. Moreover, PHGDH deficiency is exactly synonymous with PHOSPHOGLYCERATE DEHYDROGENASE DEFICIENCY.

PSAT deficiency is a type of serine deficiency that is defined as a serine deficiency with a material basis in deficiency of phosphoserine aminotransferase. It is characterized by low concentrations of serine and glycine in plasma and cerebrospinal fluid. Furthermore, PSAT deficiency has an exact synonym: Phosphoserine aminotransferase deficiency.

PSPH deficiency is a type of serine deficiency characterized by a deficiency of phosphoserine phosphatase, which impedes the synthesis of L-serine. Furthermore, PSPH deficiency is exactly synonymous with both PSPHD and Phosphoserine phosphatase deficiency.

Tyrosinemia type II, also known as Oculocutaneous tyrosinemia or Richner-Hanhart syndrome, is a specific form of tyrosinemia. It is characterized as an amino acid metabolic disorder that intersects with diseases located in zones of the skin and the liver. This condition is classified as both a skin disease and a liver disease. The disease has a notable phenotype of palmoplantar hyperkeratosis and hypertyrosinemia, along with symptoms such as keratitis. Tyrosinemia type II's definition highlights its material basis in the deficiency of hepatic tyrosine aminotransferase located in the liver. This deficiency is marked by keratitis, painful palmoplantar hyperkeratosis, mental retardation, and elevated serum tyrosine levels.

Tyrosinemia Type I is a type of Tyrosinemia and is also a type of condition that at least has the phenotype of hypertyrosinemia. It is defined as a Tyrosinemia that has a material basis in the deficiency of the enzyme fumarylacetoacetate hydrolase, which results in an increase in fumarylacetoacetate. This increase inhibits previous steps in tyrosine degradation, leading to an accumulation of tyrosine in the body. Additionally, Tyrosinemia Type I has the exact synonym "hepatorenal tyrosinemia."

Tyrosinemia type III is a type of tyrosinemia and also falls under the category of conditions that exhibit the phenotype of hypertyrosinemia. It is defined as a tyrosinemia that has its material basis in the deficiency of 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvate dioxygenase, which disrupts the breakdown of tyrosine.
Glycogen metabolism disorder is a type of carbohydrate metabolic disorder, defined as a carbohydrate metabolism disorder characterized by the abnormal accumulation or depletion of liver glycogen.

Chanarin Dorfman syndrome is a type of lipid storage disease characterized by the accumulation of triglycerides in the cytoplasm of leukocytes, muscle, liver, fibroblasts, and other tissues. It is also known by its exact synonym, neutral lipid storage disease.

Coenzyme Q10 deficiency disease is a type of mitochondrial metabolism disease and is defined as a mitochondrial metabolism disease characterized by a deficiency of CoQ10 resulting from reduced biosynthesis. Moreover, it has the exact synonym "COENZYME Q10 DEFICIENCY, PRIMARY."

Vitamin B12 deficiency is a type of vitamin metabolic disorder that also falls under the category of conditions characterized by an abnormal vitamin B12 level. It is defined as a vitamin metabolic disorder resulting from low blood levels of vitamin B12. Furthermore, this deficiency is exactly synonymous with cobalamin deficiency and hypocobalaminemia.

Methylmalonic aciduria and homocystinuria type cblE is a type of methylmalonic acidemia characterized by megaloblastic anemia, lethargy, failure to thrive, developmental delay, intellectual deficit, and seizures. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the MTRR gene on chromosome 5p15, leading to an inborn error of vitamin B12 metabolism.

Methylmalonic aciduria and homocystinuria type cblG is a type of methylmalonic acidemia. This condition is defined as a methylmalonic acidemia characterized by megaloblastic anemia, lethargy, failure to thrive, developmental delay, intellectual deficit, and seizures. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the MTR gene located on chromosome 1q43, causing an inborn error of vitamin B12 metabolism.

Congenital intrinsic factor deficiency is a type of physical disorder and a specific kind of vitamin B12 deficiency, which also falls under diseases that have their basis in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a vitamin B12 deficiency characterized by megaloblastic anemia due to the absence of gastric intrinsic factor, leading to abnormal vitamin B12 absorption. Additionally, congenital intrinsic factor deficiency is exactly synonymous with hereditary intrinsic factor deficiency.

X-linked monogenic disease is identical to the intersection of a disease and something that at least has a material basis in some X-linked inheritance. This disease is a type of monogenic disease. Furthermore, X-linked monogenic disease is defined as a monogenic disease that has its material basis in mutations in genes on the X chromosome.

An autosomal dominant disease is the same as something that is both a disease and has at least a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is a type of autosomal genetic disease. Furthermore, an autosomal dominant disease is defined as an autosomal genetic disease that is characterized by the presence of one disease-associated mutation of a gene, which is sufficient to cause the disease.

An autosomal recessive disease is the same as something that is both a disease and at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is a type of autosomal genetic disease. Furthermore, an autosomal recessive disease is defined as an autosomal genetic disease that is characterized by the presence of two mutated copies of the gene, both of which must be present for the disease or trait to develop.

Y-linked monogenic disease is a type of monogenic disease that is defined as a monogenic disease with its material basis in mutations on the Y chromosome. It is the same as something that intersects with a disease and something that at least has a material basis in Y-linked inheritance.

Autosomal genetic disease is equivalent to an entity that intersects with both a disease and an entity that has at least a material basis in autosomal inheritance. Additionally, autosomal genetic disease is categorized as a type of monogenic disease. It is defined as a monogenic disease that has a material basis in a mutation in a single gene located on one of the non-sex chromosomes.

Qazi Markouizos syndrome is a type of syndrome that is defined as a syndrome characterized by hypotonia, congenital fiber type disproportion, and dysharmonic skeletal maturation. This syndrome has phenotypes that include hypotonia and dysharmonic delayed bone age. Furthermore, Qazi Markouizos syndrome is exactly synonymous with Dysharmonic skeletal maturation - muscular fibre disproportion and Qazi-Markouizos syndrome.

Alcohol dependence is a type of substance dependence and is defined as a substance dependence characterized by tolerance, withdrawal symptoms, increasing use, persistent desire to decrease consumption, time spent obtaining or recovering from alcohol caused by a physical and psychological dependence on alcohol. Furthermore, alcohol dependence has the exact synonym alcoholism.
Nicotine dependence is a type of substance dependence and is characterized by a physical dependence on nicotine. This condition is also referred to as tobacco use disorder.

Mature T cell and NK cell lymphoma is a type of T cell non-Hodgkin lymphoma, which is defined as a T-cell non-Hodgkin lymphoma that has its material basis in mature T lymphocytes and natural killer cells. It also has the exact synonyms NK-T cell lymphoma and mature T-cell and natural killer cell lymphoma.
Anaplastic large cell lymphoma is a type of non-Hodgkin lymphoma, defined as a non-Hodgkin lymphoma involving aberrant T-cells.

Diffuse large B cell lymphoma is a type of B cell lymphoma and has the definition of being a B-cell lymphoma that is a cancer of B cells, presenting as an aggressive tumor which can arise in virtually any part of the body. Additionally, it has the exact synonym DLBCL.

Mantle cell lymphoma is a type of B-cell lymphoma and is defined as a B-cell lymphocytic neoplasm. This condition arises from CD5 positive antigen-naive pregerminal center B-cells within the mantle zone that surrounds normal germinal center follicles.

Marginal zone lymphoma is a type of B-cell lymphoma. It is defined as a B-cell lymphoma arising from the marginal zone of lymphoid tissues characterized by the presence of small to medium-sized atypical lymphocytes. This condition is also exactly synonymous with marginal zone B-cell lymphoma and marginal zone lymphoma itself.
Peripheral T cell lymphoma, a type of mature T cell and NK cell lymphoma, is defined as a group of T-cell lymphomas that develop away from the thymus.

Splenic marginal zone lymphoma is a type of marginal zone lymphoma, bone marrow cancer, and spleen cancer. It is characterized by a condition where the disease is located in both the spleen and the bone marrow. Furthermore, it is defined as a marginal zone B-cell lymphocyte located in the spleen, comprised of B-cells in place of white pulp.

T cell large granular lymphocyte leukemia is a type of T cell acute lymphoblastic leukemia. It is defined as a T-cell acute lymphocytic leukemia that exhibits an unexplained, chronic (greater than 6 months) elevation in large granular lymphocytes (LGLs) in the peripheral blood. This condition is also exactly synonymous with Large granular lymphocytic leukaemia, Large granular lymphocytic leukemia, and T-cell large granular lymphocyte leukaemia.

Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis type 8 is a specific type of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis. It is defined as an amyotrophic lateral sclerosis that has its material basis in a mutation in the VAPB gene on chromosome 20. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with ALS8 and amyotrophic lateral sclerosis 8.

Cerebellar ataxia is a type of hereditary ataxia, as well as a type of cerebellar disease, and it falls under the category of diseases that have their location in the cerebellum. Additionally, cerebellar ataxia is defined as a hereditary ataxia characterized by ataxia originating in the cerebellum.

Ataxia with oculomotor apraxia type 1 is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia. It is defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia that is characterized by progressive cerebellar ataxia including oculomotor apraxia, severe neuropathy, and hypoalbuminemia. This condition has its material basis in the autosomal recessive inheritance of a mutation in the APTX gene.

Spinocerebellar ataxia with axonal neuropathy 2 is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia. It is defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by the onset of ataxia between the ages of three and thirty, including axonal sensorimotor neuropathy, cerebellar atrophy, and elevated alpha-fetoprotein. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SETX gene located on chromosome 9q34.13. Oculomotor apraxia is common but not universal in this condition. Spinocerebellar ataxia with axonal neuropathy 2 is also exactly synonymous with several other terms: AOA2, SCAN2, SCAR1, ataxia with oculomotor apraxia type 2, autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 1, autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia with axonal neuropathy 2, and spinocerebellar ataxia with axonal neuropathy type 2.

Deafness Dystonia Optic Neuronopathy Syndrome is a type of mitochondrial metabolism disease that is also characterized by a specific structural variant related to diseases. It is defined as a mitochondrial metabolism disease characterized by early-onset hearing loss, movement problems, impaired vision, behavior problems, and has its material basis in mutations in the TIMM8A gene, which results in abnormal protein transport within the mitochondria. This syndrome is known by various exact synonyms, including Deafness Dystonia Optic Atrophy Syndrome, Dystonia Deafness Syndrome, Jensen Syndrome, Mohr-Tranebjaerg Syndrome, and Deafness Dystonia Syndrome, all of which refer to the same condition.
Metabolic acidosis is a type of acquired metabolic disease, which is characterized by the excessive production of acid.

Myotonic dystrophy type 2 is a type of myotonic disease and is characterized as a myotonic disease. It is also a type of condition that includes, at the very least, the symptom of some muscle weakness. The definition of myotonic dystrophy type 2 is a myotonic disease that is characterized by myotonia and progressive, proximal muscle wasting and weakness affecting the skeletal and smooth muscles of the neck, shoulders, elbows, and hips. This condition has a material basis in the autosomal dominant inheritance of the CNBP (ZNF9) gene, which contains an expansion of a CCTG repeat in intron one.
